il sentences on 21 April.\n* 9 April \u2013 [[United Overseas Bank]] and [[OCBC Bank]] announced that fees for their shared ATMs will be waived until the  to raise awareness of the scheme, in place since 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Boon|first1=Rachael|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/free-cross-bank-atm-withdrawals-at-ocbc-uob|title=Free cross-bank ATM withdrawals at OCBC, UOB|date=10 April 2017|website=The Straits Times|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 10 April \u2013 The [[Ministry of Culture, Community and Youth]] announced that [[Esplanade \u2013 Theatres on the Bay|The Esplanade]] will be building a new mid-size waterfront theatre. Costing $30 million, the venue can seat 550 people and will be completed by 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/arts/new-30-million-waterfront-theatre-for-esplanade|title=New $30 million waterfront theatre for Esplanade|date=2017-04-10|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n* 16 April \u2013 The [[Ministry of National Development (Singapore)|Ministry of National Development]] unveils Remaking our Heartland plans for Woodlands, with the vision \"Star of the North\". It will have new residential blocks in the north, as well as six new attractions including business parks, recreational facilities, a new hospital park and new linkways.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Zaccheus|first1=Melody|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/woodlands-to-transform-into-star-destination-of-the-north-with-new-housing|title=Woodlands to transform into 'star destination of the North' with new housing, recreational and business facilities|date=16 April 2017|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418211233/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/woodlands-to-transform-into-star-destination-of-the-north-with-new-housing|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 18 April \u2013 Woodlands Health Campus begins construction works, which will be ready by 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/woodlands-health-campus-will-add-1800-beds-and-use-technology-for-better-patient|title=Woodlands Health Campus will add 1,800 beds and use technology for better patient care|date=2017-04-18|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> \n* 20 April \u2013 \n**The first four sets of [[Junior college (Singapore)|junior colleges]] will be merged from 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/education/8-junior-colleges-among-28-schools-to-be-merged|title=8 junior colleges among 28 schools to be merged|date=2017-04-21|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n**[[Lazada Group|Lazada]] launched the LiveUp programme in preparation for Amazon's impending launch in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=New e-commerce membership programme LiveUp launches to pre-empt Amazon entry |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/new-e-commerce-membership-programme-liveup-launches-to-pre-empt-amazon-entry |publisher=The Straits Times |date=20 April 2017 |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 22 April \u2013 \n**The [[Ministry of National Development (Singapore)|Ministry of National Development]] unveils Remaking our Heartland plans for Toa Payoh, with the vision \"Our Charming Toa Payoh\". Two new housing areas will be built, along with more dragon replicas, two new parks, initiatives for the arts and heritage, and amenities for the elderly.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lin|first1=Melissa|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/toa-payoh-makeover-to-include-quirky-street-furniture-new-public-housing-projects|title=New public housing projects and mini-dragons in Toa Payoh facelift|date=22 April 2019|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408193838/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/toa-payoh-makeover-to-include-quirky-street-furniture-new-public-housing-projects|archive-date=8 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**The 10&nbsp;km Tanah Merah Coast Road extension, which has on-road cycling lanes, opens to traffic. The extension replaces the Changi Coast Road, closing for [[Changi Airport|airport]] expansion works.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Adrian |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/new-10km-on-road-cycling-lane-on-extended-tanah-merah-coast-road |title=New 10km on-road cycling lane on extended Tanah Merah Coast Road to open on April 22 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 27 April - The one-way Sentosa Gateway Tunnel is opened to traffic after a two-year delay. The tunnel can only support cars due to a height constraint of 3.5 metres.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltagov/en/pressroom/sentosa-gateway-tunnel-to-open-on-27-april-2017.html |title=Sentosa Gateway Tunnel to Open on 27 April 2017 |website=LTA |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Christopher |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/delayed-sentosa-tunnel-to-open-on-april-27 |title=Delayed Sentosa Gateway Tunnel to open on April 27 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Adrian |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/one-way-sentosa-gateway-tunnel-to-ease-congestion-opens |title=One-way Sentosa Gateway Tunnel to ease congestion opens |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=27 April 2017}}</ref>\n* 29 April \u2013 \n**The [[Ministry of National Development (Singapore)|Ministry of National Development]] unveils Remaking our Heartland plans for Pasir Ris, with the vision \"Our Urban Sanctuary\". Among them include a new mixed-use development with a bus interchange, several new linkways including a 1.2km Central Greenway, new flats near the sea, and improved neighbourhood facilities.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Tan|first1=Audrey|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sun-sand-sea-resort-living-in-pasir-ris-under-rejuvenation-plans|title=Sun, sand, sea: Resort living in Pasir Ris under HDB rejuvenation plans|date=29 April 2017|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321152820/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sun-sand-sea-resort-living-in-pasir-ris-under-rejuvenation-plans|archive-date=21 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**Elections for the [[Football Association of Singapore]] (FAS) leadership were held, with Lim Kia Tong and Bill Ng as contenders. Lim Kia Tong's team wins in a landslide. Meanwhile, the [[Singapore Police Force|police]] had raided the FAS and Bill Ng's football clubs over alleged misuse of funds.<ref>{{cite web |title=FAS Elections: Lim Kia Tong is new president after 30\u201313 win over Bill Ng |url=https://www.todayonline.com/sports/football/team-lkt-have-won-fas-elections |publisher=Todayonline |date=29 April 2017 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Police raid offices of FAS, 3 football clubs; Bill Ng says will 'fully cooperate' with probe into suspected misuse of funds |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/football/football-sportsg-files-police-report-over-alleged-misuse-of-funds-at-bill-ngs |publisher=The Straits Times |date=20 April 2017 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 1 May \u2013 The Smart Nation and Digital Government Office (SNDGO) is formed to speed up digital initiatives with expertise from [[Ministry of Finance (Singapore)|Ministry of Finance]], [[Ministry of Communications and Information]] and [[Smart Nation|Smart Nation Programme Office]]. [[Government Technology Agency|GovTech]] is now under the [[Prime Minister's Office (Singapore)|Prime Minister's Office]], together forming the Smart Nation and Digital Government Group (SNDGG).<ref>{{cite web |title=Government reorganises to 'turbo charge' smart nation projects |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/tech/government-reorganises-to-turbo-charge-smart-nation-projects |publisher=The Straits Times |date=20 March 2017 |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 3 May \u2013 Fox+ is launched by [[Fox Networks Group Asia Pacific|Fox]] as a streaming service.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yeo |first1=Sonia |url=https://www.todayonline.com/entertainment/fox-launches-streaming-service-singapore |title=Fox launches streaming service in Singapore |website=Today |date=3 May 2017 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 4 May \u2013 A fire breaks out in a building at Toh Guan, causing one death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/woman-54-dies-after-fire-breaks-out-in-building-opposite-imm-in-jurong-east|title=Woman, 54, dies after fire breaks out in building opposite IMM in Jurong East|date=2017-05-04|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> Subsequent investigations by the [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] found that the building's [[cladding (construction)|cladding]] is flammable and 39 buildings used similar cladding. As a result, 3 cladding brands are found to be unsafe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/36-buildings-may-have-combustible-cladding-that-doesn-t-meet-9153588|title=36 buildings may have combustible cladding that doesn't meet safety standards; police investigating|date=2017-08-24|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/parliament/37-buildings-identified-with-unsafe-cladding-removal-required-by-9205594|title=37 buildings identified with unsafe cladding; removal required by end-October|date=2017-09-11|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/unsafe-cladding-removed-from-17-buildings-2-more-non-compliant-9481450|title=Unsafe cladding removed from 17 buildings, 2 more non-compliant cladding models identified|date=2017-12-08|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>\n* 8 May \u2013 A debate on milk prices ensued in Parliament after The Straits Times reported in March that milk prices more than doubled over the past decade.<ref>{{cite web |title=Milk powder price woes: Average cost up by 120% in 10 years |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/milk-powder-price-woes |website=The Straits Times |date=24 March 2017 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Govt moving to ensure formula milk prices are kept in check |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-guidelines-boost-competitiveness-infant-formula-market |website=Today |date=8 May 2017 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> Two days later, the [[Competition Commission of Singapore]] found that brand loyalty and demand for premium brands drove milk power prices up.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cccs.gov.sg/media-and-consultation/newsroom/media-releases/formula-milk-market-inquiry-findings |title=CCS\u2019s Findings From the Market Inquiry into the Supply of Formula Milk |website=CCS (now CCCS) |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Koh |first1=Valerie |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/firms-capitalised-parents-brand-loyalty-penchant-premium-formula-milk-report |title=Milk brands use premium image, consumer behaviour to drive prices up: CCS |website=Today |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=10 May 2017}}</ref> In response, the [[Agri-Food and Veterinary Authority of Singapore]] announced new advertising guidelines that disallows nutrition and health claims, coupled with attractive images, and encourage breastfeeding.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Abu Baker |first1=Jalelah |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/nutrition-and-health-claims-to-be-prohibited-on-formula-milk-ava-8832674 |title=Nutrition and health claims to be prohibited on formula milk: AVA |website=Channel NewsAsia |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=10 May 2017}}</ref> In addition, various supermarket chains have introduced affordable milk brands, which are Einmilk (a made-in-Singapore milk brand),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tay |first1=Tiffany Fumiko |title=Made-in-Singapore infant milk powder launched, costs under $40 for 800g tin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/made-in-singapore-infant-milk-powder-launched-costs-under-40-for-800g-tin |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=30 May 2017}}</ref> Australia's Own,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tay |first1=Tiffany Fumiko |title=FairPrice launches Australian milk formula range priced under $35 for a 900g tin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/fairprice-launches-australian-milk-formula-range-priced-under-35-for-a-900g-tin |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=15 June 2017}}</ref> Nature One,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Idlyko |title=Sheng Siong launches affordable infant formula from Australia |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/sheng-siong-launches-new-australian-formula-milk-range |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=Today |date=24 August 2017}}</ref> [[NTUC FairPrice|FairPrice Gold]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kok |first1=Xing Hui |title=NTUC FairPrice launches house brand formula milk, prices start from $27 for 900g tin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ntuc-fairprice-launches-house-brand-formula-milk |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=20 September 2017}}</ref> and [[Blackmores]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Blackmores launches formula milk product in Singapore |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/blackmores-launches-formula-milk-product-in-singapore-9401554 |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 12 May \u2013 [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS) and [[Nanyang Technological University]] (NTU) suffered a [[cyberattack]] on their servers.<ref>{{cite web |title=NUS, NTU hit by cyber-attacks targeting Govt info, research data |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/nus-ntu-hit-sophisticated-cyber-attacks |publisher=Todayonline |date=12 May 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> \n* 16 May \u2013 A fire broke out at [[Singapore Changi Airport|Changi Airport T2]], causing 40 flights to be delayed and shutting operations for more than four hours.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fire at Changi T2 leaves thousands stranded |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/changi-t2-evacuated-due-fire |publisher=Todayonline |date=16 May 2017 |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 24 May \u2013 Three [[special education]] schools for those with [[autism]] will expand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/3-special-education-schools-to-expand-to-take-in-more-students-8879340|title=3 special education schools to expand to take in more students with autism|date=2017-05-24|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref> \n* 27 May \u2013 An [[Apple Store]] opens in [[Orchard Road]], a first in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening of Apple's first Singapore store attracts hundreds |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/opening-of-apple-s-first-singapore-store-attracts-hundreds-8887900 |publisher=CNA |date= 27 May 2017 |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 28 May \u2013 [[Bencoolen Street]] is relaunched as a car-lite road. [[Personal transporter|Personal Mobility Devices]] and [[foldable bikes]] are now allowed on public transport from 1 June, after a six-month trial. A cycling network in the city is also planned too.<ref>{{cite web |title=PMDs, foldable bikes, allowed on public transport after trial |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/personal-mobility-devices-foldable-bikes-allowed-public-transport-after-trial |website=Todayonline |date=28 May 2017 |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Plans unveiled for cycling network in the city, foldable bikes to be allowed on public transport all day |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transpor