imes.com/singapore/national-day-rally-2017-soft-drink-companies-pledge-to-reduce-sugar-in-drinks |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=20 August 2017}}</ref> with seven drink companies pledging to lower sugar content in drinks to 12 percent two days later.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seven drink companies pledge to reduce sugar in beverages to 12% or less by 2020 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/seven-drink-companies-pledge-to-reduce-sugar-in-beverages-to-12-or-less-by-2020 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 June 2019 |date=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n* 21 August \u2013 \n**10 US marines perished after destroyer USS John S. McCain collided with an oil tanker Alnic MC east of Singapore at 5:24am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/20/asia/us-navy-destroyer-collision-singapore/index.html|title=Navy continues search for sailors, wants answers|last=Lendon|first=Brad|date=21 August 2017|work=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824074149/http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/20/asia/us-navy-destroyer-collision-singapore/index.html|archive-date=24 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All the bodies are found on 28 August.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Audrey |title=Remains of all 10 sailors missing from USS John S. McCain collision found: US 7th Fleet |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/remains-of-all-10-sailors-missing-from-uss-john-s-mccain-collision-found-us-7th-fleet |website=The Straits Times |date=28 August 2017 |accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n**Touche, a biometric payment method part of the POSB Smart Buddy programme, will be an option for students to pay for items in school from 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/biometric-payment-system-to-be-an-option-in-schools-in-2018-9142490 |title=Biometric payment system to be an option in schools in 2018 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 22 August \u2013 [[Alipay]] will be launched in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=AliPay to launch local wallet for Singapore |url=https://www.todayonline.com/business/impact/alipay-launch-local-wallet-singapore-soon |website=Todayonline |date=22 August 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> Since then, [[Grab (company)|Grab]], [[NETS (company)|NETS]], [[Razer Inc.|Razer]], among other companies have announced plans to set up cashless systems.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ride-hailing app Grab launches e-payment and fund transfer system |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/tech/ride-hailing-app-grab-launches-e-payment-and-fund-transfer-system |website=The Straits Times |date=30 August 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NETSpay\">{{cite web |title=New app lets users pay by Nets \u2013 using their phones |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-app-lets-users-pay-by-nets-using-their-phones |website=The Straits Times |date=20 October 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Razer submits proposal for unified e-payment system |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/tech/razer-submits-proposal-for-unified-e-payment-system |website=The Straits Times |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> \n* 24 August \u2013 The [[Singapore Tourism Board]] and [[Economic Development Board]] launch the ''[[Passion Made Possible]]'' campaign replacing ''YourSingapore'', used since 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/media-centre/media-releases/stb-and-singapore-economic-development-board-launch-passion-made-possible-brand-for-singapore.html |title=Singapore Tourism Board and Singapore Economic Development Board launch Passion Made Possible Brand for Singapore |website=STB, EDB |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kok |first1=Xing Hui |last2=Leow |first2=Annabeth |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-new-international-brand-by-stb-and-edb-passion-made-possible |title=Singapore's new international brand by STB and EDB: Passion Made Possible |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=24 August 2017}}</ref>\n* 25 August \u2013 \n**A masterplan for Jurong Lake District is released by the [[Urban Redevelopment Authority]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-homes-jobs-lifestyle-in-jurong-lake-district|title=New homes, jobs, lifestyle in Jurong Lake District|date=31 August 2017|work=The Straits Times|url-status=live|language=en|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Mediacorp]] announced that it will acquire [[Singapore Press Holdings]]'s (SPH) stakes in Mediacorp TV (at 20 percent) and Mediacorp Press (at 40 percent) for [[S$]]18 million, which SPH will divest. This comes after Mediacorp announced that it will stop publishing the [[Today\u00a0(Singapore newspaper)|Today]] paper and go fully digital. In addition, Mediacorp will stop publishing any soft copy or digital format of Today that is similar to a hardcopy newspaper for five years.<ref>{{cite web |title=SPH to divest stakes in Mediacorp entities |url=https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/3283 |website=SPH |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mediacorp buys SPH\u2019s minority shareholdings of its entertainment television and newspaper businesses |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/corporate/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/mediacorp-buys-sph-s-minority-shareholdings-of-its-entertainment-9157914 |website=Mediacorp |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TODAY moves to a fully digital future |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/today-moves-to-a-fully-digital-future-9157934 |website=Mediacorp |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Yahya |first1=Yasmine |title=SPH to divest stakes in Mediacorp TV and Press while Today newspaper will cease print edition and go fully digital |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/bu