2013 The third stage of the [[Downtown MRT line]] (spanning from [[Fort Canning MRT station|Fort Canning]] to [[Expo MRT station|Expo]]) begins operations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Choo |first1=Cynthia |title=Downtown Line 3 to open on Oct 21 |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/downtown-line-3-open-oct-21 |website=Today |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Christopher |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/downtown-line-3-officially-opened-khaw-announces-plans-to-make-transfers-between |title=Downtown Line 3 officially opens; Khaw Boon Wan announces review of fares incurred when switching between stations |date=20 October 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=21 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021005252/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/downtown-line-3-officially-opened-khaw-announces-plans-to-make-transfers-between |archive-date=21 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 26 October - A new version of the [[Singapore passport]] is launched with new designs featuring six Singapore landmarks and new security features.<ref>{{cite web |title=New design for Singapore passport with additional security features: ICA |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-design-for-singapore-passport-with-additional-security-features-ica |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=31 December 2019 |date=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n* 30 October \u2013 [[The Float @ Marina Bay]] will be renamed to NS Square to acknowledge the contributions of National Servicemen.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marina Bay floating platform to be redeveloped to serve as primary venue for National Day Parade  |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/marina-bay-floating-platform-to-be-redeveloped-to-serve-as-9358392 |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=13 June 2019 |date=30 October 2017}}</ref> \n* 31 October \u2013 [[Singapore Changi Airport Terminal 4|Changi Airport Terminal 4]] begins operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Changi Airport\u2019s Terminal 4 to open on Oct 31 |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/nine-airlines-operate-changi-airport-t4-set-open-oct-31 |website=Today |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=6 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 6 November \u2013 Radio station 938LIVE is rebranded to [[CNA938|938Now]].\n* 7 November \u2013 Amendments are passed to raise the [[smoking age]] from 18 to 21 in stages, as well as ban people from buying, using and owning imitation tobacco products such as e-cigarettes, e-cigars and e-pipes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/legal-age-for-smoking-to-be-gradually-raised-from-18-to-21-9383644|title=Legal age for smoking to be gradually raised from 18 to 21|work=CNA|access-date=28 April 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n* 8 November \u2013 All healthcare providers will soon be required to contribute to the National Electronic Health Record, an online health record in operation since 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/national-electronic-health-record-mandatory-clinics-9385666|title=National electronic patient database soon to be mandatory for healthcare providers|date=2017-11-08|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n* 11 November \u2013 The first active aging hub officially opened in Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abdullah |first1=Zhaki |title=Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital officially opens first active ageing hub |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/kwong-wai-shiu-hospital-officially-opens-first-active-ageing-hub |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n* 15 November \u2013 A [[Joo Koon train collision|train collision]] along the [[East West MRT Line]] between [[Joo Koon MRT station|Joo Koon]] and [[Gul Circle MRT station|Gul Circle]]; this was only the second train collision in the MRT history to have happen in its 30-year history, after the 1993 [[Clementi rail accident]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/smrt-collision-second-incident-in-mrts-30-year-history|title=SMRT collision second incident in MRT's 30-year history|date=15 November 2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201045029/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/smrt-collision-second-incident-in-mrts-30-year-history|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 16 November \u2013 All new homes are required to have [[smoke detectors]] (also known as Home Fire Alarm Device (HFAD)) from June 2018, allowing for early fire alerts. Existing home owners are encouraged to install such devices.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Jun Sen |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/smoke-detectors-mandatory-in-all-new-homes-from-june-2018-existing-homeowners-also-urged |title=Smoke detectors mandatory in all new homes from June 2018; existing home owners also urged to comply |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 20 November \u2013 The second phase of the Deep Tunnel Sewerage System starts construction. It will mainly serve western Singapore, to be completed by 2025.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/work-starts-on-65b-deep-underground-tunnels-to-transport-used-water-freeing-up|title=Work starts on $6.5b deep underground tunnels to transport used water, freeing up land above for redevelopment|date=20 November 2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 23 November \u2013 Those born before 1 January 1962 will be able re-register their NRIC in an optional exercise come next year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheow |first1=Sue-Ann |title=Optional NRIC re-registration for those born before Jan 1, 1962 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/optional-nric-re-registration-for-those-born-before-jan-1-1962 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=27 December 2019 |date=23 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 24 November \u2013 The Punggol Polyclinic opens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/punggol-polyclinic-to-open-on-nov-24|title=Punggol Polyclinic to open on Nov 24 |publisher=The Straits Times|date=22 November 2017|accessdate=12 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 25 November \u2013 [[National Parks Board|NParks]] announced that [[Sembawang Hot Spring Park]] will be developed into a public park for everyone to enjoy. The works will finish in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sembawang-hot-spring-to-be-developed-into-1-hectare-park-by-2019-9439366|title=Sembawang Hot Spring to be developed into 1-hectare park by 2019|date=25 November 2017|work=CNA|access-date=5 July 2019|language=en-SG}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 1 December \u2013 [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] ambulances can now run red lights and make unauthorised U-turns during emergencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/ambulances-red-lights-unauthorised-u-turns-scdf-9382756 |title=Ambulances can legally run red lights and make unauthorised U-turns from Dec 1 |website=Channel NewsAsia |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Seow |first1=Bei Yi |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/ambulances-to-be-exempted-from-rules-that-prohibit-running-red-lights-unauthorised-u-turns |title=Ambulances to be allowed to run a red light and make unauthorised U-turns |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 8 December \u2013 Zero Mobile launches in Singapore as the second [[mobile virtual network operator]] (MVNO).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tham |first1=Irene |title=New virtual telco Zero Mobile to launch with unusual promotion |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/tech/new-virtual-telco-zero-mobile-to-launch-with-unusual-promotion |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 9 December \u2013 The 5-year Bus Service Enhancement Programme (BSEP) is completed, costing [[S$]]1.1b. The enhancements injected 1,000 buses and introduced 80 new services.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zaccheus |first1=Melody |title=$1.1b enhancement of bus services complete |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/11b-enhancement-of-bus-services-complete |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 12 December \u2013 \n**[[BlueSG]] launches Singapore's first electric car sharing programme.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore's first electric car-sharing service rolls out with 80 vehicles |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-s-first-electric-car-sharing-service-rolls-out-with-80-9492380 |website=CNA |date=12 December 2017 |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n**The Government has decided to partially conserve [[Dakota Crescent]], one of the oldest housing estates in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Partial conservation of Dakota Crescent gives heritage enthusiasts hope |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/partial-conservation-dakota-crescent-gives-heritage-enthusiasts-hope |website=Today |accessdate=5 May 2019 |date=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 15 December \u2013 After a week's delay, the first Prudential Marina Bay Carnival opens as Singapore's biggest carnival.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/marina-bay-carnival-opens-after-weeks-delay |title=Marina Bay carnival opens after week's delay |website=The Straits Times |date=15 December 2017 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> The carnival runs for about four months until 1 April 2018. By then, a total of 1.4 million people have visited the Carnival.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Cheryl |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/14-million-people-visited-the-prudential-carnival-which-ended-its-run-on |title=1.4 million people visited the Prudential Carnival which ended its run on April 1 |website=The Straits Times |date=3 April 2018 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 18 December - The [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]] will introduce e-PR system for permanent residency applications, first announced on 2 November.<ref>{{cite web |title=ICA to roll out electronic system for permanent residency applications |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/ica-to-roll-out-electronic-system-for-permanent-residency-9367982 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=31 December 2019 |date=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 19 December \u2013 [[Singapore Power]] announced that the North-South, East-West and Jurong Island Cable Tunnels will progressively start operations from end-2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-s-deepest-cable-tunnel-system-to-transmit-electricity-9510330|title=Singapore's deepest cable tunnel system to transmit electricity from end-2018|date=19 December 2017|work=CNA|access-date=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 20 December \u2013 Parking.sg is extended to those using motorcycles and heavy vehicles, making it available for all vehicle users at all car parks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/parking-sg-app-to-be-available-for-motorcycles-heavy-vehicles-9509384 |title=Parking.sg app to be available for motorcycles, heavy vehicles from Dec 20 |website=Channel NewsAsia |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 22 December \u2013 [[Keppel Corporation|Keppel O&M]] agrees to pay up to US$422m in fines for a bribery case to US, Brazilian and Singapore authorities in a plea deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/keppel-om-to-pay-us422m-in-fines-to-settle-bribery-probe|title=Keppel O&M to pay US$422m in fines to settle bribery probe|date=23 December 2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924145628/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/keppel-om-to-pay-us422m-in-fines-to-settle-bribery-probe|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=live|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n*16 January \u2013 [[Amin Nasir]], football player (b. 1968).\n*19 January \u2013 Juanita Melson, DJ and MRT announcer (b. 1944).<ref>{{cite web |title=Former voice of MRT announcements Juanita Melson dies |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/former-voice-of-mrt-announcements-juanita-melson-dies |publisher=The Straits Times |date=23 January 2017 |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n*26 January \u2013 Tan See Lai, educator, newscaster (b. 1934).<ref>{{cite web |title=Dozens pay respects to pioneer educator, newscaster Tan See Lai |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/dozens-pay-respects-to-pioneer-educator-newscaster-tan-see-lai-7561898 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=29 January 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n*4 February \u2013 [[Fong Swee Suan]], trade unionist (b. 1931).<ref>{{cite web |title=Former leftist trade unionist Fong Swee Suan dies, aged 85 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/former-leftist-trade-unionist-fong-swee-suan-dies-aged-85 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=5 February 2017 |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fong Swee Suan |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2013-07-29_173512.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n*27 February \u2013 [[Sin Kek Tong]], opposition veteran, founder of [[Singapore People's Party]] (b. 1944).<ref>{{cite web |title=Opposition veteran and Singapore People's Party founder Sin Kek Tong dies |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/opposition-veteran-and-singapore-peoples-party-founder-sin-kek-tong-dies |publisher=The Straits Times |date=1 March 2017 |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n*17 April \u2013 [[Othman Wok]], politician and ambassador (b. 1924).<ref>{{cite web |title=Othman Wok, member of independent Singapore's first Cabinet, dies aged 92 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/othman-wok-member-of-independent-singapores-first-cabinet-dies-aged-92 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=17 April 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Othman Wok |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_995_2009-07-01.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n*22 April \u2013 [[Rufino Soliano]], musician (b. 1932).<ref>{{cite web |title=Rufino Soliano |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2015-03-17_093353.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n*11 July - [[Maurice Baker (Singapore)|Maurice Baker]], academic, diplomat (b. 1920).<ref>{{cite web |title=Maurice Baker |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1538_2009-09-10.html |website=NLB |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n*7 September \u2013 [[Duncan Watt]], writer, newscaster (b. 1942).<ref>{{cite web |title=Writer and former newscaster Duncan Watt dies, aged 74 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/writer-and-former-newscaster-duncan-watt-has-died |publisher=The Straits Times |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2017]]\n*[[History of Singapore]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|2017 in}}\n\n[[Category:2017 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:2017 in Southeast Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2010s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2017 by country|Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFebruary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "Gilad Atzmon", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gilad Atzmon<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}\n| image=Gilad Atzmon.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Atzmon in concert, February 2007\n| birth_name = Gilad Atzmon\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|9}}\n| birth_place = Tel Aviv, Israel\n| known_for = Music, political activism\n| education = [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]], [[University of Essex]]\n| occupation = Musician, novelist\n| website = {{url|gilad.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Gilad Atzmon''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}, {{IPA-he|\u0261i\u02c8lad at\u0361s\u02c8mon|}}; born 9 June 1963) is a British [[jazz]] saxophonist, novelist, political activist, and writer.<ref name=\"Urbain\">Karen Abi-Ezzi, 'Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon,' in Olivier Urbain (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA93&dq=Atzmon+renounced+Israeli+citizenship ''Music and Conflict Transformation: Harmonies and Dissonances in Geopolitics,''] [[I. B. Tauris]], 2015 pp.93\u2013103, p. 93</ref><ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/><ref name=\"gilchrist222\">{{cite news|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/39I-thought-music-could-heal.3804991.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000|title='I thought music could heal the wounds of the past. I may have got that wrong'|last=Gilchrist|first=Jim|date=22 February 2008|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=Lewis>John Lewis [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/06/gilad-atzmon-israel-jazz-interview#history-byline \"Manic beat preacher\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 March 2009</ref><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Richard|year=2005|title=Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich|url-access=registration|publisher=Penguin Books| location = London | isbn = 0-141-00646-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich/page/23 23]}}</ref>\n\nAtzmon has written novels, journalistic pieces for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref>Examples of Gilad Atzmon in [[CounterPunch]]:[https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/09/18/vengeance-barbarism-and-tarantino-s-inglourious-basterds/ Vengeance, Barbarism and Tarantino's Inglourious Basterds], 18 September 2009; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/08/28/the-most-common-mistakes-of-israelis/ Collective Self-Deception: The Most Common Mistakes of Israelis], 28 August 2003; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/10/thinking-outside-of-the-secular-box/ The Left and Islam: Thinking Outside of the Secular Box], 10\u201312 July 2009.</ref> ''Uruknet'',<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://uruknet.info/?p=m31096&s1=h1 Purim Special, From Esther to AIPAC], Uruknet, 3 March 2007.</ref> ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',<ref>Example of Gilad Atzmon in ''The Palestine Telegraph'': [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/jewish-ideology-and-world-peace-by-gilad-atzmon.html 'Israeli Ideology and World Peace,'] 7 June 2010.</ref>  and polemical works on [[Jewish identity]]. His criticisms of [[Zionism]], Jewish identity, and Judaism, as well as his controversial views on [[Holocaust denial]] and [[Jewish history]], have led to allegations of antisemitism.<ref>[[Nick Lowles (activist)|Nick Lowles]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20131205131225/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr 'GILAD ATZMON: Supporting Holocaust deniers and spreading hatred,'] [[Hope Not Hate]] blog 24 November 2011</ref><ref name=Disavow>{{cite web|title=Palestinian writers, activists disavow racism, anti-Semitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/palestinian-writers-activists-disavow-racism-anti-semitism-gilad-atzmon|publisher=Electronic Intifada|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Not Quite \"Ordinary Human Beings\" \u2014 Anti-Imperialism and the Anti-Humanist Rhetoric of Gilad Atzmon |url=https://mronline.org/2012/02/28/ga280212-html/ |publisher=Monthly Review |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAtzmon was born in a [[secular Jew]]ish family in Tel Aviv, Israel, [[Ashkenazi]] on his father's side,<ref name=\"Beauty\" /> and grew up in Jerusalem.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/haunted-by-ghosts-1.319263 |title=Haunted by Ghosts |first=Yaron |last=Frid |date=15 October 2010 |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=12 January 2018 }}</ref> His great-grandmother was a victim of World War II, but he refuses to assign her death a special [[Holocaust]] status.<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA175  ''The Wandering Who,'']  p. 175 \"Historical narratives do not need the protection of the law and political lobbies. It took me years to grasp that my great-grandmother wasn\u2019t made into a \u2018soap\u2019 or a \u2018lampshade\u2019 as I was taught in Israel. She probably perished of exhaustion, typhus or maybe even by mass shooting. This was indeed bad and tragic, but not that different from the fate of many millions of Ukrainians, on learning the real meaning of communism\".</ref> His grandfather was, he states, a commander in the paramilitary [[Irgun]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate in Palestine]], who subscribed to the [[Iron Wall (essay)|doctrines]] of [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]], hated Germans, despised the British, was angry with Palestinians for living on land that God had given to Jews, and loathed Jewish leftists.<ref name = WanderingBook /> For Atzmon he was a 'veteran [[Zionist political violence|Zionist terrorist]]', and he himself grew up in what he describes as a 'happy childhood'<ref>. Silvia Cattori [http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-wandering-who/2011/9/27/silvia-cattori-interviews-gilad-atzmon.html 'Interview with Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon.com 27 September 2011</ref> imbued with a spirit of 'militant enthusiasm.'<ref name = WanderingBook />\n\nAtzmon first became interested in the British variety of [[jazz]] when he came across some recordings of it in a British record shop in Jerusalem in the 1970s, and found inspiration in the work of [[Ronnie Scott]] and [[Tubby Hayes]] and regarded London as \"the Mecca of Jazz.\"<ref name=\"JazzHot\"/> However, at 17, while readying himself for induction into the army, he happened to hear a radio broadcast of a recording of [[Charlie Parker]]'s ''[[Charlie Parker with Strings|With Strings]]'' and was swept off his feet. Atzmon has said of the album that he \"loved the way the music is both beautiful and subversive&nbsp;\u2013 the way he basks in the strings but also fights against them.\"<ref name=Lewis/> He skipped school to visit Jerusalem's Piccadilly Records outlet, and bought up every [[Bebop]] recording they stocked. Two days later, he purchased a saxophone.<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nAtzmon was [[Conscription in Israel|conscripted]] into the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) in June 1981. He began his service as a combat medic and participated in the [[1982 Lebanon War]]. Aztmon was transferred to a position within the [[Israel Defense Forces Orchestra]] and spent most of his military service in the [[Israeli Air Force]] orchestra. He explains this as a reflection of the fact that '\u2019(p)laying scales at the speed of light seemed to me far more important than killing Arabs in the name of Jewish suffering.\u2019 Three weeks before the end of his military service, in the wake of the war, his troupe visited an IDF detention camp at [[Ansar, Lebanon]]. He later wrote that this was a 'life-changing' experience, coming into direct contact with the conditions of captured Palestinians, some locked in [[solitary confinement]] in what he took at first to be 1 metre square concrete boxes for guard dogs. During a guided tour, he states that, as he peered across the barbed wire at the POWs, he felt that \u2018the place was a concentration camp. The inmates were the 'Jews', and I was nothing but a \u2018Nazi\u2019.'<ref name = WanderingBook/> After he was demobilised, he travelled to Europe in December 1984, living as a [[Street performer|busker]].<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nIn the following years, he trained at the [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]] in Jerusalem.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|work=People|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> During the late 1980s and 1990s Atzmon was a popular [[session musician]] and producer, recording extensively and performing with Israeli artists such as: [[Yehuda Poliker]], [[Yardena Arazi]], Si Himan, [[Meir Banai]] and [[Ofra Haza]]. Additionally, he started the first incarnation of the \"Gilad Atzmon Quartet\" and a group named \"Spiel Acid Jazz Band\" with fellow Israeli Jazz musicians, and performed regularly at the [[Red Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref name=haaretz />\n\nIn 1994, disenchanted with the implications of the [[Oslo Accords]], Atzmon immigrated to the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"RainLore bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rainloresworldofmusic.net/Artists/Artists_A-D/Atzmon_Gilad.html|title=Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|date=21 March 2003|publisher=Rainlore's World of Music}}</ref>{{deadlink|date=April 2020}} attending the [[University of Essex]]<ref>[http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm University of Essex news release dated 14 December 2007 notes Atzmon is a \"graduate\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422032736/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}, Essex.ac.uk; accessed 27 February 2016.</ref> and earning a master's degree in Philosophy,<ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/> while landing a residency as musician at the Irish [[Black Lion, Kilburn|Black Lion pub]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]].<ref name = WanderingBook/> He has lived subsequently in the UK,<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> becoming a British citizen in 2002<ref name=\"St. Clair\"/> and renouncing his Israeli citizenship.<ref name=\"Urbain\"/>\n\n==Music==\nWhile Atzmon's main instrument is the alto saxophone, he also plays soprano, tenor and baritone saxophones and clarinet, [[Sol (instrument)|sol]], [[zurna]] and flute.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\" /> Atzmon's jazz style has been described as [[bebop]]/[[hard bop]], with forays into [[free jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]], and seemingly inspired by [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=\"RainLore bio\" /> Atzmon sometimes plays the alto and soprano sax simultaneously.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/>\n\nAtzmon's works have also explored the music of the Middle East, North Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|title=GILAD ATZMON&nbsp;\u2013 MUSICIAN, COMPOSER, PRODUCER, EDUCATOR, WRITER|accessdate=28 October 2008|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2007|publisher=Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221120611/http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|archivedate=21 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Atzmon told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he draws on [[Arabic music]] which he says cannot be notated like western music but must be internalised, which he calls \"reverting to the primacy of the ear\". Atzmon's musical method has been to play with notions of cultural identity, flirting with genres such as tango and [[klezmer]] as well as various Arabic, Balkan, Gypsy and [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] folk forms. Atzmon's recordings deliberately differ from his live shows. \"I don't think that anyone can sit in a house, at home, and listen to me play a full-on bebop solo. It's too intense. My albums need to be less manic.\"<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Collaborations and groups===\nAtzmon joined the veteran [[punk rock]] band [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] in 1998, and continued with the Blockheads after Dury's death.<ref>Stephen Robb, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6253257.stm \"The old Blockheads shows go on\"], [[BBC News]], 25 January 2007.</ref><ref>Sara Greek, [http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm Blockheads come to Hertford Corn Exchange] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206100511/http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm |date=6 December 2013 }}, [[Hertfordshire Mercury]], 28 October 2011.</ref> He has recorded and performed with [[Shane MacGowan]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Robert Wyatt]] and [[Paul McCartney]].<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/><ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\"/> He has recorded two albums with Robert Wyatt, who describes him as \"one of the few musical geniuses I've ever met\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has collaborated, recorded and performed with musicians from all around the world, including the Palestinian singer, [[Reem Kelani]], Tunisian singer and [[oud]] player [[Dhafer Youssef]], violinist Marcel Mamaliga, accordion player Romano Viazzani, bassist Yaron Stavi, violinist and trumpet-violin player, Dumitru Ovidiu Fratila, and Guillermo Rozenthuler on vocals.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> He played tenor saxophone and clarinet on one track, \"Anisina\", on the 2014 Pink Floyd album, ''[[The Endless River]]''. He has worked with leading bands as a musical producer.<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], [http://www.tourdates.co.uk/ London Tour Dates], 5 October 2007.</ref>\n\nAtzmon founded the Orient House Ensemble band in London in 2000 with [[Asaf Sirkis]] on drums, Frank Harrison on piano and Oli Hayhurst on bass. In 2003 Yaron Stavi replaced Hayhurst. In 2009 Eddie Hick replaced Sirkis.<ref name=Ensemble>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-orient-house-ensemble/ Orient House Ensemble description at Gilad Atzmon home page.]</ref><ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/14/asaf-sirkis-letting-go-review Asaf Sirkis Trio: Letting Go \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 14 October 2010.</ref>  The group was named after [[Orient House]], the former [[East Jerusalem]] headquarters of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], later seized by the [[Israeli Defense Forces]].<ref name=Searle>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 Gilad Atzmon and The Orient House Ensemble] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107195523/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 |date=7 November 2017 }}, [[Morning Star (UK newspaper)]], 14 November 2011.</ref><ref>Jack Massarik, \"Gilad Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble\", [[Evening Standard]], 16 January 2006.</ref> The band has recorded eight albums. Orient House announced a 40-date tour in 2010.<ref name=Searle/><ref name=Fordham>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/05/gilad-atzmon-orient-house-ensemble-review Gilad Atzmon Orient House Ensemble \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Wyatt]], who has said that Atzmon combines \"great artistry with a sense of the intrinsically non-racialist philosophy that's implicit in jazz,\"<ref>Lester Paul [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/26/best-band-rock-pop \"So who is top of the pops\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 June 2010.</ref> worked with Atzmon and others on his album ''[[Comicopera]]'' (2007).<ref>Chris Jones, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gwcz A national treasure makes another peerless album], [[BBC]], 5 October 2007.</ref> Wyatt collaborated with Atzmon and Ros Stephens, as well as lyricist [[Alfreda Benge]], on the album ''For the Ghosts Within'' (2010), released on [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]].<ref>Andy Gill, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-wyatt--atzmon--stephen-for-the-ghosts-within-domino-2102994.html Album: Wyatt, Atzmon, Stephen, For The Ghosts Within (Domino)], [[The Independent]], 8 October 2011.</ref><ref>Alex Hudson, [https://exclaim.ca/music/article/robert_wyatt_unveils_new_collaborative_album \"Robert Wyatt Unveils New Collaborative Album\"], [[Exclaim!]], 8 July 2010</ref>\n\nAtzmon produced and arranged two albums for [[Sarah Gillespie]] ''Stalking Juliet ''(2009) and ''In The Current Climate ''(2011). Both albums were critically acclaimed.<ref name=\"Guardian\">John Fordham [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/10/sarah-gillespie-stalking-juliet-review \"Stalking Juliet review\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 April 2009</ref><ref name=\"Mail\">{{Cite web |url=http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday |title=\"Current Climate Review\", ''Mail on Sunday'', January 2011. |access-date=15 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826172200/http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday/ |archive-date=26 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has toured extensively as a member of Sarah Gillespie's band, playing saxophone, clarinet and accordion.<ref name=\"Metro\">[http://www.metro.co.uk/music/852007-jazz-your-cd-collection-up \"Robert Shaw, Guitarist Keeps Her Finger on the Pulse\"], Metro.co.uk, 6 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon is on the creative panel of the [[Global Music Foundation]],<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/> a non-profit organization formed in December 2004 which runs residential educational and performance workshops and events in different countries around the world.<ref name=\"GMF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad mAtzmon|accessdate=23 October 2017|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> and also offers personal workshops to students.<ref name=\"Atzmon-Workshop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/education-1/|title=MUSIC EDUCATION|accessdate=3 January 2018|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2015|publisher=Gilad Atzmon}}</ref> A musical transcription of ten saxophone solos by Atzmon was released in 2010.<ref>Chris Gumbley, [http://www.gumblespublications.co.uk/saxophone-solos/ Gilad Uncovered: 10 Transcriptions], Gumbles Publications, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Reviews and awards===\nAtzmon and his ensemble have received favorable reviews from the ''[[Financial Times]]'', ''[[The Scotsman]]'', ''[[Birmingham Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Bacon|first=Peter|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CULTURE%3A+Arts+reviews%3A+Activist+with+quotes+and+plenty+to+say%3B+Gilad...-a0127526728|title=Activist with quotes and plenty to say; Gilad Atzmon CBSO Centre|work=Birmingham Post| date=24 January 2005|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon web site].</ref> Reviews of his 2007 album ''Refuge'' included:\n:''[[Manchester Evening News]]'': \"The individuality of the music is extraordinary. No one is more willing to serve his music with raw political passion, and that curious [[Hazzan|cantor]]-like tone on clarinet is immediately arresting, like [[Artie Shaw]] writhing in his death throes.\"<ref>Alan Brownlee, [http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/world_music/s/1015/1015003_gilad_atzmon__the_orient_house_ensemble__refuge_enja.html Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble&nbsp;\u2013 Refuge (Enja)], [[Manchester Evening News]], 30 August 2007.</ref>\n:[[BBC]]: \"...the OHE is finding its voice in an increasingly subtle blend of East and West, that\u2019s brutal and beautiful.\"<ref>Kathryn Shackleton, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/5vp2/ Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble, Refuge], [[BBC]], 1 October 2007.</ref>\n\nIn February 2009 ''[[The Guardian]]'' jazz critic [[John Fordham (jazz critic)|John Fordham]] reviewed Atzmon's newest album ''In loving memory of America'' which was described by Atzmon as \"a memory of America I had cherished in my mind for many years\". It includes five standards and six originals \"inspired by the sumptuous harmonies and impassioned sax-playing of [[Charlie Parker|(Charlie) Parker]]'s late-40s recordings with classical strings\".<ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/27/gilad-atzmon-loving-memory-america \"Gilad Atzmon: In Loving Memory of America\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 February 2009.</ref> Music journalist John Lewis has praised much of Atzmon's work and described Atzmon as \"one of London's finest saxophonists\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon was the recipient of the [[HMV]] ''Top Dog Award'' at the [[Jazz of Birmingham|Birmingham International Jazz Festival]] in 1996\u201398.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> Gilad Atzmon's ''Exile'' was BBC jazz album of the year in 2003.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/3107607.stm Jazz winners span generations], BBC, 30 July 2003.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nAtzmon has defined himself variously as a \"[[secular Jew]]\",<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> a \"proud self-hating Jew\"  in the style of [[Otto Weininger]],<ref name=\"Panayides\" >Theo Panayides, [https://web.archive.org/web/20100223072804/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/living/wandering-jazz-player/20100221 'Wandering jazz player,'], [[Cyprus Mail]], 21 February 2010: \"My ethical duty is to say the things that I know and feel. I\u2019m an artist. Do you know.. this is something I learned from Otto Weininger, the Austrian philosopher. He was a clever boy, killed himself when he was 21. ..He was definitely a proud self-hating Jew! I\u2019m not a self-hating Jew: I\u2019m a proud self-hating Jew! It\u2019s a big difference\u2026 I celebrate my hatred towards everything I represent \u2013 or better to say [everything] I\u2019m associated with\".</ref> an \"ex-Jew\",<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/a-new-jewish-goal-by-gilad-atzmon.html A New Jewish Goal], at his personal web site.</ref> \"a Jew who hates Judaism\",<ref>{{cite news|last=\u05d7\u05dc\u05d9\u05dc\u05d9|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d8\u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df|url=http://article.yedioth.co.il/default.aspx?articleid=5448|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=9 November 2011|language=Hebrew|quote=\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05e9\u05dd \u05d0\u05ea \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9 \u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d6\u05db\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05ea \u05de\u05d2\u05d3\u05dc\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d7\u05df \u05db\u05dc \u05d0\u05e1\u05e4\u05e7\u05d8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05db\u05d9. (As a Jew who hates Judaism, I put myself under a magnifying glass and examine every Jewish aspect in me).}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halily|first=Yaniv|title=The protocols of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4147243,00.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=14 November 2011}}</ref> and \"a Hebrew-speaking Palestinian\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/>\n\nAtzmon writes and edits for the website, Palestine Think Tank.<ref name=Lewis/> He told interviewer Theo Panayides: \"I don't write about politics, I write about ethics. I write about Identity. I write a lot about the [[Jewish Question]]&nbsp;\u2013 because I was born in the Jew-land, and my whole process in maturing into an adult was involved with the realisation that my people are living on stolen land.\"<ref name=\"Panayides\"/> Atzmon has said that his experience in the military of \"my people destroying other people left a big scar\" and led to his decision that he was deluded about Zionism. He has condemned \"Jewishness\" as \"very much a supremacist, racist tendency\", but he has also stated that \"I don't have anything against Jews in particular and you won't find that in my writings\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> Regarding the one-state solution, Atzmon concedes that such a state probably would be controlled by [[Islamist]]s, but says, \"That's their business\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has compared \"the Jewish Ideology\" to that of the [[Nazis]] and has described Israel's policy toward the Palestinians as [[genocide]].<ref name=\"gibson\"/> \n\n===Novels===\nAtzmon's ''[[A Guide to the Perplexed]]'', published in 2001, is set in a 2052 in which Israel has been replaced by a Palestinian state. It largely reviews memoirs of the alienated Israeli Gunther Wunker's rise to fame as a \"peepologist\", or voyeur. The perplexed are defined as \"the unthinking Chosen\" who \"cling to clods of earth that don't belong to them.\" The novel excoriates what it describes as the commercialization of the Holocaust and \"argues that the Holocaust is invoked as a kind of reflexive propaganda designed to shield the Zionist state from responsibility for any transgression against Palestinians.\"<ref name=\"St. Clair\">[[Jeffrey St. Clair]],[https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/07/17/gilad-atzmon-s-a-guide-to-the-perplexed/ 'Gilad Atzmon's \"A Guide to the Perplexed\",'] [[CounterPunch]] 17 July 2003</ref>\n\nMatthew J. Reisz, a reviewer for ''[[The Independent]]'', wrote that \"As a viciously black satire on Israeli life\" the book \"is grandiose, childish and nasty, but with just enough connection with reality to give it a certain unsettling power\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Reisz|first=Matthew J.|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/a-guide-to-the-perplexed-by-gilad-atzmon-trans-philip-simpson-609999.html|title=A Guide to the Perplexed, by Gilad Atzmon, trans. Philip Simpson|work=The Independent|date=7 December 2002|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} Darren King in ''[[The Observer]]'' noted of this \"provocative debut novel\" that it is \"odd to mix knob gags with highly serious assertions\", but thought it works because \"Atzmon writes with so much style and his gags are so hilarious\".<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Darren|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/featuresreviews.guardianreview16|title=Mr. Peepology|work=The Observer|date=25 January 2003|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', \"Atzmon clearly wants to provoke, but his approach is so familiar that few readers will take the bait.\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-85242-826-6 \"A Guide to the Perplexed\"], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', 31 March 2003.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's second novel, ''My One and Only Love'', was published in 2005 and features as a protagonist a trumpeter who chooses to play only one note (extremely well), as well as a spy who uncovers Nazi war criminals and locks them inside double bass cases which then tour permanently in the protagonist's orchestra's luggage.<ref>Sholto Byrnes. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/talking-jazz-529796.html \"Talking Jazz\"], ''The Independent'', 25 March 2005</ref> The book is also a comedic take on \"Zionist espionage and intrigue\" which explores \"the personal conflict between being true to one\u2019s heart and being loyal to The Jews\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2004/10/01/gilad_event_feature.shtml \"Gilad Atzmon's Orient House Ensemble \u2013 The Junction\"], BBC Cambridgeshire, 3 June 2005.</ref>\n\n===''The Wandering Who?''===\nIn 2011, [[Zero Books]] published Atzmon's book ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics'', stating that it \"examines Jewish identity politics and Jewish contemporary ideology using both popular culture and scholarly texts.\"<ref name = WanderingBook>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=rTbtBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&lpg=PT7 ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics''], Zero Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84694-875-6}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jean Bricmont]], in his preface for the French edition, ''La Parabole d\u2019Esther'', Atzmon starts by making three definitions of the word 'Jewish': (a) it may refer to adherents of Judaism, and he has no quarrel with them; (b) secondly, it may refer to ethnic Jews, and, likewise, he sees no problem in that; (c) thirdly, it can refer to a third category, those who, without being particularly religious, place great emphasis on their Jewish \"identity\" as something more important than their basic membership of the human race.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" >[[Jean Bricmont]], [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/counterpunch-print-edition-in-defense-of-gilad-atzmon-by-jea.html  'In Defense of Gilad Atzmon By Jean Bricmont,'] Counterpunch April 2012 print edition, cited on Atzmon's blog.</ref> Bricmont then adds that it is very easy to mount a case to 'prove' Atzmon is an antisemite by consistently construing his criticisms of (c) as though they were aimed as (a) or (b) or both.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" /> \n\n[[Marc H. Ellis]],  professor of Jewish studies at [[Baylor University]], likens Atzmon's rhetorical extremism and harsh censure of Jews to the [[Prophet|prophetic voices]] of the [[Old Testament]], arguing that, for Atzmon, [[Diaspora|diasporic]] Jews are asked to construct their identity on the basis of the [[State of Israel]] and the [[Holocaust]], an identity he regards as without foundation. He adds that Atzmon considers charges that he is antisemitic as 'last ditch attempts' to validate that identity. In Ellis's view, there may be, in the perceived anxiety in these repeated attacks, a reflection of the same anxiety Atzmon himself arguably embodies.<ref name=\"Ellis\" >[[Marc H. Ellis]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=doN-AwAAQBAJ&dq=Marc+Ellis%2BGilad+Atzmon&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y  ''Future of the Prophetic: Israel's Ancient Wisdom Re-presented,''] [[Fortress Press]], 2014 pp.331\u2013332.</ref><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/the-new-jewish-prophet.html  'The New Jewish Prophet,'] 24 June 2014.</ref> {{efn|Ellis also notes that Atzmon considers the bible 'bogus'.<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> Atzmon himself cites evidence 600 passages in the OT are violent, and argues that this 'lethal spirit of the scriptures has infused the essence of modern Jewish political discourse,' underwriting in his view even the secular mindset of military commanders conducting war in Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.<ref>G. Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA122 ''The Wandering Who,''] 2011 p.122.</ref>}}\n\nTen authors published by Zero Books, including [[Laurie Penny]] and [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]], criticised the publisher publicly for releasing the book, arguing:<blockquote>The thrust of Atzmon's work is to normalise and legitimise anti-Semitism. We do not believe that Zero's decision to publish this book is malicious. Atzmon's ability to solicit endorsements from respectable figures such as [[Richard Falk]] and [[John Mearsheimer]] shows that he is adept at muddying the waters both on his own views and on the question of anti-Semitism. But at a time when dangerous forces are attempting to racialise political antagonisms, we think the decision is grossly mistaken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leninology.blogspot.com/2011/09/zero-authors-statement-on-gilad-atzmon.html|title=Zero Authors Statement on Gilad Atzmon|publisher=Lenin's Tomb|date=26 September 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nMearsheimer has said that \"There is no question that the book is provocative, both in terms of its central argument and the overly hot language that Atzmon sometimes uses. But it is also filled with interesting insights that make the reader think long and hard about an important subject.\"<ref>Stephen Walt, [http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The New Republic]]'', [[Alan Dershowitz]] criticized Mearsheimer and Falk for recommending the book<ref name=\"Dershowitz\">Alan Dershowitz, [http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/97030/atzmon-wandering-who-anti-semitism-israel \"Why are John Mearsheimer and Richard Falk Endorsing a Blatantly Anti-Semitic Book?\"], ''The New Republic'', 4 November 2011.</ref> and challenged them to a public debate.<ref name=\"Dershowitz\"/> Falk rejected Dershowitz's call to debate.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} Atzmon offered to debate Dershowitz at \"any time\".<ref>Gilad Atzmon at Gilad Atzmon website, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/dershowitz-lies-and-glitches-by-gilad-atzmon.html Dershowitz\u2019 Lies and Glitches], 9 November 2011 and [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/if-dershowitz-wants-a-debate-i-will-meet-him-any-time.html \"If Dershowitz Wants a Debate, I Will Meet Him Any Time\"], 23 October 2011.</ref> He called various criticisms \"a typical [[Hasbara]] smear & intimidation campaign.\u201d<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/goldberg-vs-mearsheimer-by-gilad-atzmon.html Goldberg vs. Mearsheimer], Gilad Atzmon website, 25 September 2011.</ref> Atzmon replied to the MacDonald review referenced by Dershowitz, writing that his book \"is a study of Jewish identity politics and Jewish culture, it is not concerned with Jewish ethnicity or racial origins.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-supremacists-on-the-wandering-who.html \"Supremacists on 'The Wandering Who'\"], Gilad.co.uk, 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\n==Allegations of antisemitism==\nSeveral of Atzmon's statements regarding Jews and Judaism have led to allegations of antisemitism. \n\n===Campaigners===\nThe [[Anti-Defamation League]] describes Atzmon as \"antisemitic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/profiles/gilad-atzmon|title=Gilad Atzmon|publisher=ADL|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today,'' published in 2012 by Hope not Hate, [[Nick Lowles]] wrote: \"Despite being Jewish himself, Atzmon has promoted Holocaust deniers and claims that the established history of the Holocaust is misleading. He attacks Jewish identity in a way that would clearly be recognised as racist if it were about any other minority identity and claims that people might think that Hitler was right about the Jews because of their behaviour today. He tells crude antisemitic jokes and mocks any concerns about antisemitism.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111105903/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-01-11|date=December 2012|publisher=[[Hope not Hate]]|page=9|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\nIn a 2005 opinion piece, [[David Aaronovitch]] criticized Atzmon for his essay \"On Anti-Semitism\" and for allegedly defending [[Israel Shamir]], circulating an essay by Paul Eisen defending [[Ernst Z\u00fcndel]]'s right to think, speak, and write as he pleases, and supporting many aspects of Z\u00fcndel's Holocaust denial theories.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\">{{cite news|last=Aaronovitch|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-did-the-far-left-manage-to-slip-into-bed-with-the-jew-hating-right-766cbwpdqfd|title=How did the far Left manage to slip into bed with the Jew-hating Right?|work=The Times|location=London|date=28 June 2005|accessdate=24 February 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"onanti\">Gilad Atzmon, {{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |title=On Anti-Semitism |accessdate=27 July 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050213011436/http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |archivedate=13 February 2005 }}, originally at his personal web site, 20 December 2003.</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 opinion piece, [[David Hirsh]] criticised what he called Atzmon's \"openly anti-Jewish rhetoric\", including [[Jewish deicide]].<ref>Hirsh, David. [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/nov/30/anewmenacingcurrentisappe Openly embracing prejudice], ''The Guardian'', 30 November 2006. Hirsh also refers to the statement in [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/apr/03/nobodyhaseverclaimedthatc \"What charge?\"], \"The Guardian\", 3 April 2006.</ref> In response to a question about this, Atzmon replied \"I find it astonishing that people today happen to be offended by such accusations (i.e. about an event almost 2000 years ago.)\"<ref>[https://www.counterpunch.org/2007/02/15/quot-do-i-look-like-the-pope-quot/ \"Are You a Christian?\" \"Do I Look Like the Pope?\"&nbsp;\u2013 An Exchange Between Lenni Brenner & Gilad Atzmon], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 15 February 2007.</ref>\n\n[[Keith Kahn-Harris]] argues, in a 2017 opinion piece, that Atzmon's view of the world in ''Being In Time'' (2017) is inherently antisemitic. Kahn-Harris describes Atzmon as \"deliberately apathetic about the Holocaust and other atrocities against Jews, nodding towards without completely embracing both justification and denial\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Kahn-Harris|first=Keith|url=https://forward.com/opinion/389696/cloaked-in-pretensions-gilad-atzmons-anti-semitism-soldiers-on/|title=Cloaked In Pretensions, Gilad Atzmon\u2019s Anti-Semitism Soldiers On|work=Forward|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Zionists===\nIn 2011, David Landy, an Irish academic and former chair of the Ireland Palestine Solidarity Campaign, wrote that Atzmon's words, \"if not actually anti-Semitic, certainly border on it\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Landy|first=David|title=Jewish Identity and Palestinian Rights: Disapora Jewish Opposition to Israel|year=2011|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-84813-926-8|page=167}}</ref> \n\nA group of mainly US based Palestinian activists, including [[Ali Abunimah]], [[Naseer Aruri]], [[Omar Barghouti]], [[Nadia Hijab]] and [[Joseph Massad]], issued a statement in March 2012 calling for \"the disavowal of Atzmon by fellow Palestinian organizers, as well as Palestine solidarity activists, and allies of the Palestinian people\" and affirming that \"we regard any attempt to link and adopt antisemitic or racist language, even if it is within a self-described anti-imperialist and anti-Zionist politics, as reaffirming and legitimizing Zionism.\"<ref name=Disavow/>\n\n===Comments at talk===\nAt a talk by Richard Falk at [[London School of Economics|LSE]] in March 2017, which was being disrupted by protestors, Atzmon was alleged to have commented that Jews had been \"expelled from Germany for misbehaving\" and suggested that people should read Holocaust denier [[David Irving]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-students-told-dont-study-at-lse-by-board-president/|title=Jewish students told 'don\u2019t study at LSE' by Board president|work=Jewish News Online|date=23 March 2017|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Responses===\nAtzmon refers to charges of antisemitism as being a \"common Zionist silencing apparatus.\"<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], Interview with Gilad Atzmon in ''London Tour Dates'' magazine, 5 October 2006</ref> He denies that he is an antisemite and states that, \"Because 'Anti-Semite' is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have.\"<ref name=1001Lies>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/1001-lies-about-gilad-atzmon.html 1001 Lies About Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon com. 18 June 2011 \"I am an anti Zionist and oppose the Zionist mindset. I look at questions of Jewish identity and I do question the ties between a Jewish world view and Zionism. I refute totally that I am anti-Semite. In fact I also believe that the current concept of an Anti-Semitism is meaningless. Once the Zionists had managed to establish their Jewish state, any form of anti Jewish sentiments should be comprehended either as a private case of xenophobia or as a political retaliation to Israeli/Zionist atrocities. In other words, the title Anti-Semite became an \u2018empty signifier, i.e. a signifier with a vague, highly variable, unspecifiable or non-existent signified. It is an empty verbal utterance that exists merely to serve a political cause (very much like Blair\u2019s WMD and Bush\u2019s Axis of Evil). Because Anti-Semite is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have\".</ref> In 2009, Atzmon said \"I've got nothing against the Semite people, I don't have anything against people&nbsp;\u2014 I'm anti-Jewish, not anti-Jews.\"<ref name=\"gibson\">Gibson, Martin. \"No choice but to speak out&nbsp;\u2014 Israeli musician 'a proud self-hating Jew'\", ''The Gisborne Herald'', 23 January 2009.</ref> He added that \"Stupidly we interpreted the Nazi defeat as a vindication of the Jewish ideology and the Jewish people\"; however, \"in fact Jewish ideology and Nazi ideology were very similar.\"<ref name=\"gibson\"/> Atzmon has also stated that he does not deny the Holocaust or the \"Nazi Judeocide\u201d but insists \"that both the Holocaust and World War II should be treated as historical events rather than as religious myth. ... But then, even if we accept the Holocaust as the new Anglo-American liberal-democratic religion, we must allow people to be atheists.\u201d<ref name=\"Beauty\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|title=Beauty as a political weapon; Three in one: jazzman, writer and activist&nbsp;\u2013 A conversation with Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072556/http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|archivedate=3 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Talens\" >[[:es:Manuel Talens|Manuel Talens]],  [http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=24333 'La belleza como arma pol\u00edtica,'] [[Rebelion.org]] 19 December 2005,</ref> Atzmon has said his statements have lost him performance contracts, especially in the United States.<ref>Karen Abi-Ezzi, \"Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon\u201d, Chapter 7 of Olivier Urbain, Editor, ''Music and conflict transformation: harmonies and dissonances in geopolitics'', I.B. Tauris, 2008  [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA101&dq=urbain+atzmon+contracts&hl=en&ei=2wpFTPf2C8P88Ab03uDKDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 101].</ref> Atzmon has had conflicts with anti-Zionists who have attempted to stop his performances.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\"/><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-lieberman-and-the-jewish-political-continuum.html \"Gilad Atzmon: Lieberman and the Jewish Political Continuum\"], at Gilad Atzmon's web site, 10 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Oren Ben-Dor]] wrote in 2008 \"I am firmly convinced that these vulgar attempts at silencing of Gilad and other courageous voices offends against supremely thoughtful, compassionate and egalitarian intellectual endeavours.\"<ref>[[Oren Ben-Dor]], [https://www.counterpunch.org/2008/03/15/the-silencing-of-gilad-atzmon/ 'The Silencing of Gilad Atzmon'], [[CounterPunch]], 15 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, reviewer [[Chris Searle]] defended accusations against Atzmon's \"crude anti-zionist rhetoric\u201d, writing \"No jazz musicians have done more to honour, publicise and spread solidarity with the struggle of the Palestinians than Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble.\u201d<ref>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 Review of the book ''Jazz Jews'' by Mike Gerber] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175013/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 |date=23 October 2017 }}, ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', February 2010.</ref> \n\nIn 2011, [[John Mearsheimer]] defended Atzmon, writing with regard to the charge that Atzmon is antisemitic, \"to be perfectly clear, he has no animus toward Judaism as a religion or with individuals who are Jewish by birth. Rather, his target is the tribalism that he believes is common to most Jews, and I might add, to most other peoples as well. ... The more important and interesting issue is whether Atzmon is a self-hating Jew. Here the answer is unequivocally yes.\" \n\n[[Richard Falk]] described Atzmon \"a de-Zionized patriot of humanity\".<ref>Stephen M. Walt,[http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], 26 September 2011 (posted on Walt.Foreignpolicy.com)</ref> \n\nIn 2012, [[Norton Mezvinsky]] wrote that \"Gilad Atzmon is a critical and committed secular humanist with firm views, who delights in being provocative.\"<ref>[[Norton Mezvinsky]], [http://wrmea.org/archives/507-washington-report-archives-2011-2015/may-2012/11161-gilad-atzmon-and-the-wandering-who.html Gilad Atzmon and The Wandering Who?], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.wrmea.org/action-alert-archives/11194-engaging-gilad-atzmon.html 'Engaging Gilad Atzmon], video of Norton Mezvinsky interview with Gilad Atzmon,' [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref>\n\n==Libel suit==\nIn July 2018, Atzmon issued an apology to Gideon Falter, the chairman of the [[Campaign Against Antisemitism]] after being sued for libel. Atzmon had alleged that Falter had personally profited from fabricating antisemitic incidents. He was also liable for legal costs and damages.<ref name=\"Libel\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Ben |title=Gilad Atzmon is forced to apologise to CAA's Gideon Falter over libel |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/gideon-falter-gilad-atzmon-1.466405 |accessdate=3 July 2018 |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CAA\">{{cite web |title=Antisemitic author and saxophonist Gilad Atzmon capitulates, making humiliating apology and paying substantial damages and costs after just two hours in court against CAA |url=https://antisemitism.uk/antisemitic-author-and-saxophonist-gilad-atzmon-capitulates-making-humiliating-apology-and-paying-substantial-damages-and-costs-after-just-two-hours-in-court-against-caa/ |website=antisemitism.uk |publisher=Campaign Against Antisemitism |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The Spirit of Trane'' (Fanfare Jazz, 2017)\n*''World Peace Trio'' (Enja, 2017)\n*''Songs of the Metropolis'' (World Village, 2013)\n*''The Tide Has Changed'' (World Village, 2010)\n*''In Loving Memory of America'' (Enja, 2009)\n*''Refuge'' (Enja, 2007)\n*''Artie Fishel and the Promised Band'' (WMD, 2006)\n*''MusiK'' (Enja, 2004)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/oct/08/jazz.shopping1</ref>\n*''Exile'' (Enja, 2004)\n*''Nostalgico'' (Enja, 2001)\n*''Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble'' (Enja, 2000)\n*''Juizz Muzic'' (FruitBeard, 1999)\n*''Take It or Leave It'' (Face Jazz, 1997)\n*''Spiel: Both Sides'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel Acid Jazz Band'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel'' (In Acoustic & H.M. Acoustica, 1993)\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book |title=[[A Guide to the Perplexed]] |translator= Philip Simpson |location=London|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]] |year=2002 |isbn=1-85242-826-0}}\n*''My one and only love''. London: Saqi Books, 2005. {{ISBN|0-86356-507-7}} (pbk.). {{ISBN|978-0-86356-507-6}} (pbk.)\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C| title=The Wandering Who?: A Study of Jewish Identity Politics |publisher=[[John Hunt Publishing|Zero Books]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-84694-875-6}}\n* ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon''. London, Fanfare Press, 2015.{{ISBN|978-0993183706}} (pbk.). \n*''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', Newbold on Stour, Warwickshire: Skyscraper Publications, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1911072201}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brian Lenzo, [http://www.palestinechronicle.com/old/view_article_details.php?id=16132 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed: Each Village is a Reminder], originally published by Socialist Worker Online, 13 July 2010 (reprinted by the Palestine Chronicle).\n*Alan Maass, [https://socialistworker.org/2010/07/14/an-article-retracted An Article Retracted], Socialist Worker Online, 14 July 2010 (retraction of preceding interview).\n*[http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/eveningnews24/norwich-whats-on-guide/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=GoingOutMusic&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=WhatsOn&itemid=NOED26%20Nov%202009%2016%3A03%3A06%3A953 Interview: Gilad Atzmon] by Rob Garratt, Evening News 24, 11 November 2009.\n*[https://archive.org/details/GiladAtzmonOnArabvoices.netJune2009 Gilad Atzmon interview on ArabVoices.net], [[KPFT]], June 2009 during visit to Houston, Texas.\n*Ivan Hewett, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3667959/Gilad-Altzmon-High-flown-ecstasies-from-an-angry-man.html Gilad Altzmon: High-flown ecstasies from an angry man], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 17 September 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133806/http://middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21321 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed by Mary Rizzo], Middle East Online, July 2007.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon website]\n\n{{The Blockheads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atzmon, Gilad}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:Anti-Judaism]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism]]\n[[Category:Bebop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:The Blockheads members]]\n[[Category:British jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:British male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Writers on Zionism]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gilad Atzmon<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}\n| image=Gilad Atzmon.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Atzmon in concert, February 2007\n| birth_name = Gilad Atzmon\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|9}}\n| birth_place = Tel Aviv, Israel\n| known_for = Music, political activism\n| education = [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]], [[University of Essex]]\n| occupation = Musician, novelist\n| website = {{url|gilad.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Gilad Atzmon''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}, {{IPA-he|\u0261i\u02c8lad at\u0361s\u02c8mon|}}; born 9 June 1963) is a British [[jazz]] saxophonist, novelist, political activist, and writer.<ref name=\"Urbain\">Karen Abi-Ezzi, 'Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon,' in Olivier Urbain (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA93&dq=Atzmon+renounced+Israeli+citizenship ''Music and Conflict Transformation: Harmonies and Dissonances in Geopolitics,''] [[I. B. Tauris]], 2015 pp.93\u2013103, p. 93</ref><ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/><ref name=\"gilchrist222\">{{cite news|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/39I-thought-music-could-heal.3804991.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000|title='I thought music could heal the wounds of the past. I may have got that wrong'|last=Gilchrist|first=Jim|date=22 February 2008|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=Lewis>John Lewis [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/06/gilad-atzmon-israel-jazz-interview#history-byline \"Manic beat preacher\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 March 2009</ref><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Richard|year=2005|title=Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich|url-access=registration|publisher=Penguin Books| location = London | isbn = 0-141-00646-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich/page/23 23]}}</ref>\n\nAtzmon has written novels, journalistic pieces for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref>Examples of Gilad Atzmon in [[CounterPunch]]:[https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/09/18/vengeance-barbarism-and-tarantino-s-inglourious-basterds/ Vengeance, Barbarism and Tarantino's Inglourious Basterds], 18 September 2009; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/08/28/the-most-common-mistakes-of-israelis/ Collective Self-Deception: The Most Common Mistakes of Israelis], 28 August 2003; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/10/thinking-outside-of-the-secular-box/ The Left and Islam: Thinking Outside of the Secular Box], 10\u201312 July 2009.</ref> ''Uruknet'',<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://uruknet.info/?p=m31096&s1=h1 Purim Special, From Esther to AIPAC], Uruknet, 3 March 2007.</ref> ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',<ref>Example of Gilad Atzmon in ''The Palestine Telegraph'': [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/jewish-ideology-and-world-peace-by-gilad-atzmon.html 'Israeli Ideology and World Peace,'] 7 June 2010.</ref>  and polemical works on [[Jewish identity]]. His criticisms of [[Zionism]], Jewish identity, and Judaism, as well as his controversial views on [[Holocaust denial]] and [[Jewish history]], have led to allegations of antisemitism.<ref>[[Nick Lowles (activist)|Nick Lowles]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20131205131225/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr 'GILAD ATZMON: Supporting Holocaust deniers and spreading hatred,'] [[Hope Not Hate]] blog 24 November 2011</ref><ref name=Disavow>{{cite web|title=Palestinian writers, activists disavow racism, anti-Semitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/palestinian-writers-activists-disavow-racism-anti-semitism-gilad-atzmon|publisher=Electronic Intifada|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Not Quite \"Ordinary Human Beings\" \u2014 Anti-Imperialism and the Anti-Humanist Rhetoric of Gilad Atzmon |url=https://mronline.org/2012/02/28/ga280212-html/ |publisher=Monthly Review |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAtzmon was born in a [[secular Jew]]ish family in Tel Aviv, Israel, [[Ashkenazi]] on his father's side,<ref name=\"Beauty\" /> and grew up in Jerusalem.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/haunted-by-ghosts-1.319263 |title=Haunted by Ghosts |first=Yaron |last=Frid |date=15 October 2010 |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=12 January 2018 }}</ref> His great-grandmother was a victim of World War II, but he refuses to assign her death a special [[Holocaust]] status.<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA175  ''The Wandering Who,'']  p. 175 \"Historical narratives do not need the protection of the law and political lobbies. It took me years to grasp that my great-grandmother wasn\u2019t made into a \u2018soap\u2019 or a \u2018lampshade\u2019 as I was taught in Israel. She probably perished of exhaustion, typhus or maybe even by mass shooting. This was indeed bad and tragic, but not that different from the fate of many millions of Ukrainians, on learning the real meaning of communism\".</ref> His grandfather was, he states, a commander in the paramilitary [[Irgun]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate in Palestine]], who subscribed to the [[Iron Wall (essay)|doctrines]] of [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]], hated Germans, despised the British, was angry with Palestinians for living on land that God had given to Jews, and loathed Jewish leftists.<ref name = WanderingBook /> For Atzmon he was a 'veteran [[Zionist political violence|Zionist terrorist]]', and he himself grew up in what he describes as a 'happy childhood'<ref>. Silvia Cattori [http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-wandering-who/2011/9/27/silvia-cattori-interviews-gilad-atzmon.html 'Interview with Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon.com 27 September 2011</ref> imbued with a spirit of 'militant enthusiasm.'<ref name = WanderingBook />\n\nAtzmon first became interested in the British variety of [[jazz]] when he came across some recordings of it in a British record shop in Jerusalem in the 1970s, and found inspiration in the work of [[Ronnie Scott]] and [[Tubby Hayes]] and regarded London as \"the Mecca of Jazz.\"<ref name=\"JazzHot\"/> However, at 17, while readying himself for induction into the army, he happened to hear a radio broadcast of a recording of [[Charlie Parker]]'s ''[[Charlie Parker with Strings|With Strings]]'' and was swept off his feet. Atzmon has said of the album that he \"loved the way the music is both beautiful and subversive&nbsp;\u2013 the way he basks in the strings but also fights against them.\"<ref name=Lewis/> He skipped school to visit Jerusalem's Piccadilly Records outlet, and bought up every [[Bebop]] recording they stocked. Two days later, he purchased a saxophone.<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nAtzmon was [[Conscription in Israel|conscripted]] into the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) in June 1981. He began his service as a combat medic and participated in the [[1982 Lebanon War]]. Aztmon was transferred to a position within the [[Israel Defense Forces Orchestra]] and spent most of his military service in the [[Israeli Air Force]] orchestra. He explains this as a reflection of the fact that '\u2019(p)laying scales at the speed of light seemed to me far more important than killing Arabs in the name of Jewish suffering.\u2019 Three weeks before the end of his military service, in the wake of the war, his troupe visited an IDF detention camp at [[Ansar, Lebanon]]. He later wrote that this was a 'life-changing' experience, coming into direct contact with the conditions of captured Palestinians, some locked in [[solitary confinement]] in what he took at first to be 1 metre square concrete boxes for guard dogs. During a guided tour, he states that, as he peered across the barbed wire at the POWs, he felt that \u2018the place was a concentration camp. The inmates were the 'Jews', and I was nothing but a \u2018Nazi\u2019.'<ref name = WanderingBook/> After he was demobilised, he travelled to Europe in December 1984, living as a [[Street performer|busker]].<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nIn the following years, he trained at the [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]] in Jerusalem.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|work=People|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> During the late 1980s and 1990s Atzmon was a popular [[session musician]] and producer, recording extensively and performing with Israeli artists such as: [[Yehuda Poliker]], [[Yardena Arazi]], Si Himan, [[Meir Banai]] and [[Ofra Haza]]. Additionally, he started the first incarnation of the \"Gilad Atzmon Quartet\" and a group named \"Spiel Acid Jazz Band\" with fellow Israeli Jazz musicians, and performed regularly at the [[Red Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref name=haaretz />\n\nIn 1994, disenchanted with the implications of the [[Oslo Accords]], Atzmon immigrated to the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"RainLore bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rainloresworldofmusic.net/Artists/Artists_A-D/Atzmon_Gilad.html|title=Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|date=21 March 2003|publisher=Rainlore's World of Music}}</ref>{{deadlink|date=April 2020}} attending the [[University of Essex]]<ref>[http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm University of Essex news release dated 14 December 2007 notes Atzmon is a \"graduate\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422032736/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}, Essex.ac.uk; accessed 27 February 2016.</ref> and earning a master's degree in Philosophy,<ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/> while landing a residency as musician at the Irish [[Black Lion, Kilburn|Black Lion pub]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]].<ref name = WanderingBook/> He has lived subsequently in the UK,<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> becoming a British citizen in 2002<ref name=\"St. Clair\"/> and renouncing his Israeli citizenship.<ref name=\"Urbain\"/>\n\n==Music==\nWhile Atzmon's main instrument is the alto saxophone, he also plays soprano, tenor and baritone saxophones and clarinet, [[Sol (instrument)|sol]], [[zurna]] and flute.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\" /> Atzmon's jazz style has been described as [[bebop]]/[[hard bop]], with forays into [[free jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]], and seemingly inspired by [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=\"RainLore bio\" /> Atzmon sometimes plays the alto and soprano sax simultaneously.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/>\n\nAtzmon's works have also explored the music of the Middle East, North Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|title=GILAD ATZMON&nbsp;\u2013 MUSICIAN, COMPOSER, PRODUCER, EDUCATOR, WRITER|accessdate=28 October 2008|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2007|publisher=Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221120611/http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|archivedate=21 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Atzmon told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he draws on [[Arabic music]] which he says cannot be notated like western music but must be internalised, which he calls \"reverting to the primacy of the ear\". Atzmon's musical method has been to play with notions of cultural identity, flirting with genres such as tango and [[klezmer]] as well as various Arabic, Balkan, Gypsy and [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] folk forms. Atzmon's recordings deliberately differ from his live shows. \"I don't think that anyone can sit in a house, at home, and listen to me play a full-on bebop solo. It's too intense. My albums need to be less manic.\"<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Collaborations and groups===\nAtzmon joined the veteran [[punk rock]] band [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] in 1998, and continued with the Blockheads after Dury's death.<ref>Stephen Robb, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6253257.stm \"The old Blockheads shows go on\"], [[BBC News]], 25 January 2007.</ref><ref>Sara Greek, [http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm Blockheads come to Hertford Corn Exchange] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206100511/http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm |date=6 December 2013 }}, [[Hertfordshire Mercury]], 28 October 2011.</ref> He has recorded and performed with [[Shane MacGowan]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Robert Wyatt]] and [[Paul McCartney]].<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/><ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\"/> He has recorded two albums with Robert Wyatt, who describes him as \"one of the few musical geniuses I've ever met\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has collaborated, recorded and performed with musicians from all around the world, including the Palestinian singer, [[Reem Kelani]], Tunisian singer and [[oud]] player [[Dhafer Youssef]], violinist Marcel Mamaliga, accordion player Romano Viazzani, bassist Yaron Stavi, violinist and trumpet-violin player, Dumitru Ovidiu Fratila, and Guillermo Rozenthuler on vocals.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> He played tenor saxophone and clarinet on one track, \"Anisina\", on the 2014 Pink Floyd album, ''[[The Endless River]]''. He has worked with leading bands as a musical producer.<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], [http://www.tourdates.co.uk/ London Tour Dates], 5 October 2007.</ref>\n\nAtzmon founded the Orient House Ensemble band in London in 2000 with [[Asaf Sirkis]] on drums, Frank Harrison on piano and Oli Hayhurst on bass. In 2003 Yaron Stavi replaced Hayhurst. In 2009 Eddie Hick replaced Sirkis.<ref name=Ensemble>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-orient-house-ensemble/ Orient House Ensemble description at Gilad Atzmon home page.]</ref><ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/14/asaf-sirkis-letting-go-review Asaf Sirkis Trio: Letting Go \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 14 October 2010.</ref>  The group was named after [[Orient House]], the former [[East Jerusalem]] headquarters of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], later seized by the [[Israeli Defense Forces]].<ref name=Searle>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 Gilad Atzmon and The Orient House Ensemble] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107195523/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 |date=7 November 2017 }}, [[Morning Star (UK newspaper)]], 14 November 2011.</ref><ref>Jack Massarik, \"Gilad Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble\", [[Evening Standard]], 16 January 2006.</ref> The band has recorded eight albums. Orient House announced a 40-date tour in 2010.<ref name=Searle/><ref name=Fordham>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/05/gilad-atzmon-orient-house-ensemble-review Gilad Atzmon Orient House Ensemble \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Wyatt]], who has said that Atzmon combines \"great artistry with a sense of the intrinsically non-racialist philosophy that's implicit in jazz,\"<ref>Lester Paul [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/26/best-band-rock-pop \"So who is top of the pops\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 June 2010.</ref> worked with Atzmon and others on his album ''[[Comicopera]]'' (2007).<ref>Chris Jones, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gwcz A national treasure makes another peerless album], [[BBC]], 5 October 2007.</ref> Wyatt collaborated with Atzmon and Ros Stephens, as well as lyricist [[Alfreda Benge]], on the album ''For the Ghosts Within'' (2010), released on [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]].<ref>Andy Gill, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-wyatt--atzmon--stephen-for-the-ghosts-within-domino-2102994.html Album: Wyatt, Atzmon, Stephen, For The Ghosts Within (Domino)], [[The Independent]], 8 October 2011.</ref><ref>Alex Hudson, [https://exclaim.ca/music/article/robert_wyatt_unveils_new_collaborative_album \"Robert Wyatt Unveils New Collaborative Album\"], [[Exclaim!]], 8 July 2010</ref>\n\nAtzmon produced and arranged two albums for [[Sarah Gillespie]] ''Stalking Juliet ''(2009) and ''In The Current Climate ''(2011). Both albums were critically acclaimed.<ref name=\"Guardian\">John Fordham [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/10/sarah-gillespie-stalking-juliet-review \"Stalking Juliet review\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 April 2009</ref><ref name=\"Mail\">{{Cite web |url=http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday |title=\"Current Climate Review\", ''Mail on Sunday'', January 2011. |access-date=15 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826172200/http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday/ |archive-date=26 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has toured extensively as a member of Sarah Gillespie's band, playing saxophone, clarinet and accordion.<ref name=\"Metro\">[http://www.metro.co.uk/music/852007-jazz-your-cd-collection-up \"Robert Shaw, Guitarist Keeps Her Finger on the Pulse\"], Metro.co.uk, 6 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon is on the creative panel of the [[Global Music Foundation]],<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/> a non-profit organization formed in December 2004 which runs residential educational and performance workshops and events in different countries around the world.<ref name=\"GMF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad mAtzmon|accessdate=23 October 2017|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> and also offers personal workshops to students.<ref name=\"Atzmon-Workshop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/education-1/|title=MUSIC EDUCATION|accessdate=3 January 2018|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2015|publisher=Gilad Atzmon}}</ref> A musical transcription of ten saxophone solos by Atzmon was released in 2010.<ref>Chris Gumbley, [http://www.gumblespublications.co.uk/saxophone-solos/ Gilad Uncovered: 10 Transcriptions], Gumbles Publications, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Reviews and awards===\nAtzmon and his ensemble have received favorable reviews from the ''[[Financial Times]]'', ''[[The Scotsman]]'', ''[[Birmingham Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Bacon|first=Peter|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CULTURE%3A+Arts+reviews%3A+Activist+with+quotes+and+plenty+to+say%3B+Gilad...-a0127526728|title=Activist with quotes and plenty to say; Gilad Atzmon CBSO Centre|work=Birmingham Post| date=24 January 2005|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon web site].</ref> Reviews of his 2007 album ''Refuge'' included:\n:''[[Manchester Evening News]]'': \"The individuality of the music is extraordinary. No one is more willing to serve his music with raw political passion, and that curious [[Hazzan|cantor]]-like tone on clarinet is immediately arresting, like [[Artie Shaw]] writhing in his death throes.\"<ref>Alan Brownlee, [http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/world_music/s/1015/1015003_gilad_atzmon__the_orient_house_ensemble__refuge_enja.html Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble&nbsp;\u2013 Refuge (Enja)], [[Manchester Evening News]], 30 August 2007.</ref>\n:[[BBC]]: \"...the OHE is finding its voice in an increasingly subtle blend of East and West, that\u2019s brutal and beautiful.\"<ref>Kathryn Shackleton, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/5vp2/ Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble, Refuge], [[BBC]], 1 October 2007.</ref>\n\nIn February 2009 ''[[The Guardian]]'' jazz critic [[John Fordham (jazz critic)|John Fordham]] reviewed Atzmon's newest album ''In loving memory of America'' which was described by Atzmon as \"a memory of America I had cherished in my mind for many years\". It includes five standards and six originals \"inspired by the sumptuous harmonies and impassioned sax-playing of [[Charlie Parker|(Charlie) Parker]]'s late-40s recordings with classical strings\".<ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/27/gilad-atzmon-loving-memory-america \"Gilad Atzmon: In Loving Memory of America\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 February 2009.</ref> Music journalist John Lewis has praised much of Atzmon's work and described Atzmon as \"one of London's finest saxophonists\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon was the recipient of the [[HMV]] ''Top Dog Award'' at the [[Jazz of Birmingham|Birmingham International Jazz Festival]] in 1996\u201398.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> Gilad Atzmon's ''Exile'' was BBC jazz album of the year in 2003.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/3107607.stm Jazz winners span generations], BBC, 30 July 2003.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nAtzmon has defined himself variously as a \"[[secular Jew]]\",<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> a \"proud self-hating Jew\"  in the style of [[Otto Weininger]],<ref name=\"Panayides\" >Theo Panayides, [https://web.archive.org/web/20100223072804/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/living/wandering-jazz-player/20100221 'Wandering jazz player,'], [[Cyprus Mail]], 21 February 2010: \"My ethical duty is to say the things that I know and feel. I\u2019m an artist. Do you know.. this is something I learned from Otto Weininger, the Austrian philosopher. He was a clever boy, killed himself when he was 21. ..He was definitely a proud self-hating Jew! I\u2019m not a self-hating Jew: I\u2019m a proud self-hating Jew! It\u2019s a big difference\u2026 I celebrate my hatred towards everything I represent \u2013 or better to say [everything] I\u2019m associated with\".</ref> an \"ex-Jew\",<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/a-new-jewish-goal-by-gilad-atzmon.html A New Jewish Goal], at his personal web site.</ref> \"a Jew who hates Judaism\",<ref>{{cite news|last=\u05d7\u05dc\u05d9\u05dc\u05d9|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d8\u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df|url=http://article.yedioth.co.il/default.aspx?articleid=5448|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=9 November 2011|language=Hebrew|quote=\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05e9\u05dd \u05d0\u05ea \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9 \u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d6\u05db\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05ea \u05de\u05d2\u05d3\u05dc\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d7\u05df \u05db\u05dc \u05d0\u05e1\u05e4\u05e7\u05d8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05db\u05d9. (As a Jew who hates Judaism, I put myself under a magnifying glass and examine every Jewish aspect in me).}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halily|first=Yaniv|title=The protocols of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4147243,00.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=14 November 2011}}</ref> and \"a Hebrew-speaking Palestinian\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/>\n\nAtzmon writes and edits for the website, Palestine Think Tank.<ref name=Lewis/> He told interviewer Theo Panayides: \"I don't write about politics, I write about ethics. I write about Identity. I write a lot about the [[Jewish Question]]&nbsp;\u2013 because I was born in the Jew-land, and my whole process in maturing into an adult was involved with the realisation that my people are living on stolen land.\"<ref name=\"Panayides\"/> Atzmon has said that his experience in the military of \"my people destroying other people left a big scar\" and led to his decision that he was deluded about Zionism. He has condemned \"Jewishness\" as \"very much a supremacist, racist tendency\", but he has also stated that \"I don't have anything against Jews in particular and you won't find that in my writings\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> Regarding the one-state solution, Atzmon concedes that such a state probably would be controlled by [[Islamist]]s, but says, \"That's their business\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has compared \"the Jewish Ideology\" to that of the [[Nazis]] and has described Israel's policy toward the Palestinians as [[genocide]].<ref name=\"gibson\"/> \n\n===Novels===\nAtzmon's ''[[A Guide to the Perplexed]]'', published in 2001, is set in a 2052 in which Israel has been replaced by a Palestinian state. It largely reviews memoirs of the alienated Israeli Gunther Wunker's rise to fame as a \"peepologist\", or voyeur. The perplexed are defined as \"the unthinking Chosen\" who \"cling to clods of earth that don't belong to them.\" The novel excoriates what it describes as the commercialization of the Holocaust and \"argues that the Holocaust is invoked as a kind of reflexive propaganda designed to shield the Zionist state from responsibility for any transgression against Palestinians.\"<ref name=\"St. Clair\">[[Jeffrey St. Clair]],[https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/07/17/gilad-atzmon-s-a-guide-to-the-perplexed/ 'Gilad Atzmon's \"A Guide to the Perplexed\",'] [[CounterPunch]] 17 July 2003</ref>\n\nMatthew J. Reisz, a reviewer for ''[[The Independent]]'', wrote that \"As a viciously black satire on Israeli life\" the book \"is grandiose, childish and nasty, but with just enough connection with reality to give it a certain unsettling power\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Reisz|first=Matthew J.|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/a-guide-to-the-perplexed-by-gilad-atzmon-trans-philip-simpson-609999.html|title=A Guide to the Perplexed, by Gilad Atzmon, trans. Philip Simpson|work=The Independent|date=7 December 2002|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} Darren King in ''[[The Observer]]'' noted of this \"provocative debut novel\" that it is \"odd to mix knob gags with highly serious assertions\", but thought it works because \"Atzmon writes with so much style and his gags are so hilarious\".<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Darren|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/featuresreviews.guardianreview16|title=Mr. Peepology|work=The Observer|date=25 January 2003|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', \"Atzmon clearly wants to provoke, but his approach is so familiar that few readers will take the bait.\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-85242-826-6 \"A Guide to the Perplexed\"], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', 31 March 2003.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's second novel, ''My One and Only Love'', was published in 2005 and features as a protagonist a trumpeter who chooses to play only one note (extremely well), as well as a spy who uncovers Nazi war criminals and locks them inside double bass cases which then tour permanently in the protagonist's orchestra's luggage.<ref>Sholto Byrnes. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/talking-jazz-529796.html \"Talking Jazz\"], ''The Independent'', 25 March 2005</ref> The book is also a comedic take on \"Zionist espionage and intrigue\" which explores \"the personal conflict between being true to one\u2019s heart and being loyal to The Jews\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2004/10/01/gilad_event_feature.shtml \"Gilad Atzmon's Orient House Ensemble \u2013 The Junction\"], BBC Cambridgeshire, 3 June 2005.</ref>\n\n===''The Wandering Who?''===\nIn 2011, [[Zero Books]] published Atzmon's book ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics'', stating that it \"examines Jewish identity politics and Jewish contemporary ideology using both popular culture and scholarly texts.\"<ref name = WanderingBook>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=rTbtBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&lpg=PT7 ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics''], Zero Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84694-875-6}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jean Bricmont]], in his preface for the French edition, ''La Parabole d\u2019Esther'', Atzmon starts by making three definitions of the word 'Jewish': (a) it may refer to adherents of Judaism, and he has no quarrel with them; (b) secondly, it may refer to ethnic Jews, and, likewise, he sees no problem in that; (c) thirdly, it can refer to a third category, those who, without being particularly religious, place great emphasis on their Jewish \"identity\" as something more important than their basic membership of the human race.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" >[[Jean Bricmont]], [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/counterpunch-print-edition-in-defense-of-gilad-atzmon-by-jea.html  'In Defense of Gilad Atzmon By Jean Bricmont,'] Counterpunch April 2012 print edition, cited on Atzmon's blog.</ref> Bricmont then adds that it is very easy to mount a case to 'prove' Atzmon is an antisemite by consistently construing his criticisms of (c) as though they were aimed as (a) or (b) or both.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" /> \n\n[[Marc H. Ellis]],  professor of Jewish studies at [[Baylor University]], likens Atzmon's rhetorical extremism and harsh censure of Jews to the [[Prophet|prophetic voices]] of the [[Old Testament]], arguing that, for Atzmon, [[Diaspora|diasporic]] Jews are asked to construct their identity on the basis of the [[State of Israel]] and the [[Holocaust]], an identity he regards as without foundation. He adds that Atzmon considers charges that he is antisemitic as 'last ditch attempts' to validate that identity. In Ellis's view, there may be, in the perceived anxiety in these repeated attacks, a reflection of the same anxiety Atzmon himself arguably embodies.<ref name=\"Ellis\" >[[Marc H. Ellis]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=doN-AwAAQBAJ&dq=Marc+Ellis%2BGilad+Atzmon&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y  ''Future of the Prophetic: Israel's Ancient Wisdom Re-presented,''] [[Fortress Press]], 2014 pp.331\u2013332.</ref><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/the-new-jewish-prophet.html  'The New Jewish Prophet,'] 24 June 2014.</ref> {{efn|Ellis also notes that Atzmon considers the bible 'bogus'.<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> Atzmon himself cites evidence 600 passages in the OT are violent, and argues that this 'lethal spirit of the scriptures has infused the essence of modern Jewish political discourse,' underwriting in his view even the secular mindset of military commanders conducting war in Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.<ref>G. Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA122 ''The Wandering Who,''] 2011 p.122.</ref>}}\n\nTen authors published by Zero Books, including [[Laurie Penny]] and [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]], criticised the publisher publicly for releasing the book, arguing:<blockquote>The thrust of Atzmon's work is to normalise and legitimise anti-Semitism. We do not believe that Zero's decision to publish this book is malicious. Atzmon's ability to solicit endorsements from respectable figures such as [[Richard Falk]] and [[John Mearsheimer]] shows that he is adept at muddying the waters both on his own views and on the question of anti-Semitism. But at a time when dangerous forces are attempting to racialise political antagonisms, we think the decision is grossly mistaken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leninology.blogspot.com/2011/09/zero-authors-statement-on-gilad-atzmon.html|title=Zero Authors Statement on Gilad Atzmon|publisher=Lenin's Tomb|date=26 September 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nMearsheimer has said that \"There is no question that the book is provocative, both in terms of its central argument and the overly hot language that Atzmon sometimes uses. But it is also filled with interesting insights that make the reader think long and hard about an important subject.\"<ref>Stephen Walt, [http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The New Republic]]'', [[Alan Dershowitz]] criticized Mearsheimer and Falk for recommending the book<ref name=\"Dershowitz\">Alan Dershowitz, [http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/97030/atzmon-wandering-who-anti-semitism-israel \"Why are John Mearsheimer and Richard Falk Endorsing a Blatantly Anti-Semitic Book?\"], ''The New Republic'', 4 November 2011.</ref> and challenged them to a public debate.<ref name=\"Dershowitz\"/> Falk rejected Dershowitz's call to debate.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} Atzmon offered to debate Dershowitz at \"any time\".<ref>Gilad Atzmon at Gilad Atzmon website, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/dershowitz-lies-and-glitches-by-gilad-atzmon.html Dershowitz\u2019 Lies and Glitches], 9 November 2011 and [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/if-dershowitz-wants-a-debate-i-will-meet-him-any-time.html \"If Dershowitz Wants a Debate, I Will Meet Him Any Time\"], 23 October 2011.</ref> He called various criticisms \"a typical [[Hasbara]] smear & intimidation campaign.\u201d<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/goldberg-vs-mearsheimer-by-gilad-atzmon.html Goldberg vs. Mearsheimer], Gilad Atzmon website, 25 September 2011.</ref> Atzmon replied to the MacDonald review referenced by Dershowitz, writing that his book \"is a study of Jewish identity politics and Jewish culture, it is not concerned with Jewish ethnicity or racial origins.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-supremacists-on-the-wandering-who.html \"Supremacists on 'The Wandering Who'\"], Gilad.co.uk, 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\n==Allegations of antisemitism==\nSeveral of Atzmon's statements regarding Jews and Judaism have led to allegations of antisemitism. \n\n===Campaigners===\nThe [[Anti-Defamation League]] describes Atzmon as \"antisemitic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/profiles/gilad-atzmon|title=Gilad Atzmon|publisher=ADL|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today,'' published in 2012 by Hope not Hate, [[Nick Lowles]] wrote: \"Despite being Jewish himself, Atzmon has promoted Holocaust deniers and claims that the established history of the Holocaust is misleading. He attacks Jewish identity in a way that would clearly be recognised as racist if it were about any other minority identity and claims that people might think that Hitler was right about the Jews because of their behaviour today. He tells crude antisemitic jokes and mocks any concerns about antisemitism.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111105903/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-01-11|date=December 2012|publisher=[[Hope not Hate]]|page=9|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\nIn a 2005 opinion piece, [[David Aaronovitch]] criticized Atzmon for his essay \"On Anti-Semitism\" and for allegedly defending [[Israel Shamir]], circulating an essay by Paul Eisen defending [[Ernst Z\u00fcndel]]'s right to think, speak, and write as he pleases, and supporting many aspects of Z\u00fcndel's Holocaust denial theories.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\">{{cite news|last=Aaronovitch|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-did-the-far-left-manage-to-slip-into-bed-with-the-jew-hating-right-766cbwpdqfd|title=How did the far Left manage to slip into bed with the Jew-hating Right?|work=The Times|location=London|date=28 June 2005|accessdate=24 February 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"onanti\">Gilad Atzmon, {{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |title=On Anti-Semitism |accessdate=27 July 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050213011436/http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |archivedate=13 February 2005 }}, originally at his personal web site, 20 December 2003.</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 opinion piece, [[David Hirsh]] criticised what he called Atzmon's \"openly anti-Jewish rhetoric\", including [[Jewish deicide]].<ref>Hirsh, David. [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/nov/30/anewmenacingcurrentisappe Openly embracing prejudice], ''The Guardian'', 30 November 2006. Hirsh also refers to the statement in [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/apr/03/nobodyhaseverclaimedthatc \"What charge?\"], \"The Guardian\", 3 April 2006.</ref> In response to a question about this, Atzmon replied that \"I find it astonishing that people today happen to be offended by such accusations (i.e. about an event almost 2000 years ago.)\"<ref>[https://www.counterpunch.org/2007/02/15/quot-do-i-look-like-the-pope-quot/ \"Are You a Christian?\" \"Do I Look Like the Pope?\"&nbsp;\u2013 An Exchange Between Lenni Brenner & Gilad Atzmon], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 15 February 2007.</ref>\n\n[[Keith Kahn-Harris]] argues, in a 2017 opinion piece, that Atzmon's view of the world in ''Being In Time'' (2017) is inherently antisemitic. Kahn-Harris describes Atzmon as \"deliberately apathetic about the Holocaust and other atrocities against Jews, nodding towards without completely embracing both justification and denial\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Kahn-Harris|first=Keith|url=https://forward.com/opinion/389696/cloaked-in-pretensions-gilad-atzmons-anti-semitism-soldiers-on/|title=Cloaked In Pretensions, Gilad Atzmon\u2019s Anti-Semitism Soldiers On|work=Forward|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Zionists===\nIn 2011, David Landy, an Irish academic and former chair of the Ireland Palestine Solidarity Campaign, wrote that Atzmon's words, \"if not actually anti-Semitic, certainly border on it\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Landy|first=David|title=Jewish Identity and Palestinian Rights: Disapora Jewish Opposition to Israel|year=2011|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-84813-926-8|page=167}}</ref> \n\nA group of mainly US based Palestinian activists, including [[Ali Abunimah]], [[Naseer Aruri]], [[Omar Barghouti]], [[Nadia Hijab]] and [[Joseph Massad]], issued a statement in March 2012 calling for \"the disavowal of Atzmon by fellow Palestinian organizers, as well as Palestine solidarity activists, and allies of the Palestinian people\" and affirming that \"we regard any attempt to link and adopt antisemitic or racist language, even if it is within a self-described anti-imperialist and anti-Zionist politics, as reaffirming and legitimizing Zionism.\"<ref name=Disavow/>\n\n===Comments at talk===\nAt a talk by Richard Falk at [[London School of Economics|LSE]] in March 2017, which was being disrupted by protestors, Atzmon was alleged to have commented that Jews had been \"expelled from Germany for misbehaving\" and suggested that people should read Holocaust denier [[David Irving]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-students-told-dont-study-at-lse-by-board-president/|title=Jewish students told 'don\u2019t study at LSE' by Board president|work=Jewish News Online|date=23 March 2017|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Responses===\nAtzmon refers to charges of antisemitism as being a \"common Zionist silencing apparatus.\"<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], Interview with Gilad Atzmon in ''London Tour Dates'' magazine, 5 October 2006</ref> He denies that he is an antisemite and states that, \"Because 'Anti-Semite' is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have.\"<ref name=1001Lies>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/1001-lies-about-gilad-atzmon.html 1001 Lies About Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon com. 18 June 2011 \"I am an anti Zionist and oppose the Zionist mindset. I look at questions of Jewish identity and I do question the ties between a Jewish world view and Zionism. I refute totally that I am anti-Semite. In fact I also believe that the current concept of an Anti-Semitism is meaningless. Once the Zionists had managed to establish their Jewish state, any form of anti Jewish sentiments should be comprehended either as a private case of xenophobia or as a political retaliation to Israeli/Zionist atrocities. In other words, the title Anti-Semite became an \u2018empty signifier, i.e. a signifier with a vague, highly variable, unspecifiable or non-existent signified. It is an empty verbal utterance that exists merely to serve a political cause (very much like Blair\u2019s WMD and Bush\u2019s Axis of Evil). Because Anti-Semite is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have\".</ref> In 2009, Atzmon said \"I've got nothing against the Semite people, I don't have anything against people&nbsp;\u2014 I'm anti-Jewish, not anti-Jews.\"<ref name=\"gibson\">Gibson, Martin. \"No choice but to speak out&nbsp;\u2014 Israeli musician 'a proud self-hating Jew'\", ''The Gisborne Herald'', 23 January 2009.</ref> He added that \"Stupidly we interpreted the Nazi defeat as a vindication of the Jewish ideology and the Jewish people\"; however, \"in fact Jewish ideology and Nazi ideology were very similar.\"<ref name=\"gibson\"/> Atzmon has also stated that he does not deny the Holocaust or the \"Nazi Judeocide\u201d but insists \"that both the Holocaust and World War II should be treated as historical events rather than as religious myth. ... But then, even if we accept the Holocaust as the new Anglo-American liberal-democratic religion, we must allow people to be atheists.\u201d<ref name=\"Beauty\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|title=Beauty as a political weapon; Three in one: jazzman, writer and activist&nbsp;\u2013 A conversation with Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072556/http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|archivedate=3 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Talens\" >[[:es:Manuel Talens|Manuel Talens]],  [http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=24333 'La belleza como arma pol\u00edtica,'] [[Rebelion.org]] 19 December 2005,</ref> Atzmon has said his statements have lost him performance contracts, especially in the United States.<ref>Karen Abi-Ezzi, \"Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon\u201d, Chapter 7 of Olivier Urbain, Editor, ''Music and conflict transformation: harmonies and dissonances in geopolitics'', I.B. Tauris, 2008  [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA101&dq=urbain+atzmon+contracts&hl=en&ei=2wpFTPf2C8P88Ab03uDKDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 101].</ref> Atzmon has had conflicts with anti-Zionists who have attempted to stop his performances.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\"/><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-lieberman-and-the-jewish-political-continuum.html \"Gilad Atzmon: Lieberman and the Jewish Political Continuum\"], at Gilad Atzmon's web site, 10 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Oren Ben-Dor]] wrote in 2008 \"I am firmly convinced that these vulgar attempts at silencing of Gilad and other courageous voices offends against supremely thoughtful, compassionate and egalitarian intellectual endeavours.\"<ref>[[Oren Ben-Dor]], [https://www.counterpunch.org/2008/03/15/the-silencing-of-gilad-atzmon/ 'The Silencing of Gilad Atzmon'], [[CounterPunch]], 15 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, reviewer [[Chris Searle]] defended accusations against Atzmon's \"crude anti-zionist rhetoric\u201d, writing \"No jazz musicians have done more to honour, publicise and spread solidarity with the struggle of the Palestinians than Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble.\u201d<ref>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 Review of the book ''Jazz Jews'' by Mike Gerber] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175013/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 |date=23 October 2017 }}, ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', February 2010.</ref> \n\nIn 2011, [[John Mearsheimer]] defended Atzmon, writing with regard to the charge that Atzmon is antisemitic, \"to be perfectly clear, he has no animus toward Judaism as a religion or with individuals who are Jewish by birth. Rather, his target is the tribalism that he believes is common to most Jews, and I might add, to most other peoples as well. ... The more important and interesting issue is whether Atzmon is a self-hating Jew. Here the answer is unequivocally yes.\" \n\n[[Richard Falk]] described Atzmon \"a de-Zionized patriot of humanity\".<ref>Stephen M. Walt,[http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], 26 September 2011 (posted on Walt.Foreignpolicy.com)</ref> \n\nIn 2012, [[Norton Mezvinsky]] wrote that \"Gilad Atzmon is a critical and committed secular humanist with firm views, who delights in being provocative.\"<ref>[[Norton Mezvinsky]], [http://wrmea.org/archives/507-washington-report-archives-2011-2015/may-2012/11161-gilad-atzmon-and-the-wandering-who.html Gilad Atzmon and The Wandering Who?], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.wrmea.org/action-alert-archives/11194-engaging-gilad-atzmon.html 'Engaging Gilad Atzmon], video of Norton Mezvinsky interview with Gilad Atzmon,' [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref>\n\n==Libel suit==\nIn July 2018, Atzmon issued an apology to Gideon Falter, the chairman of the [[Campaign Against Antisemitism]] after being sued for libel. Atzmon had alleged that Falter had personally profited from fabricating antisemitic incidents. He was also liable for legal costs and damages.<ref name=\"Libel\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Ben |title=Gilad Atzmon is forced to apologise to CAA's Gideon Falter over libel |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/gideon-falter-gilad-atzmon-1.466405 |accessdate=3 July 2018 |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CAA\">{{cite web |title=Antisemitic author and saxophonist Gilad Atzmon capitulates, making humiliating apology and paying substantial damages and costs after just two hours in court against CAA |url=https://antisemitism.uk/antisemitic-author-and-saxophonist-gilad-atzmon-capitulates-making-humiliating-apology-and-paying-substantial-damages-and-costs-after-just-two-hours-in-court-against-caa/ |website=antisemitism.uk |publisher=Campaign Against Antisemitism |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The Spirit of Trane'' (Fanfare Jazz, 2017)\n*''World Peace Trio'' (Enja, 2017)\n*''Songs of the Metropolis'' (World Village, 2013)\n*''The Tide Has Changed'' (World Village, 2010)\n*''In Loving Memory of America'' (Enja, 2009)\n*''Refuge'' (Enja, 2007)\n*''Artie Fishel and the Promised Band'' (WMD, 2006)\n*''MusiK'' (Enja, 2004)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/oct/08/jazz.shopping1</ref>\n*''Exile'' (Enja, 2004)\n*''Nostalgico'' (Enja, 2001)\n*''Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble'' (Enja, 2000)\n*''Juizz Muzic'' (FruitBeard, 1999)\n*''Take It or Leave It'' (Face Jazz, 1997)\n*''Spiel: Both Sides'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel Acid Jazz Band'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel'' (In Acoustic & H.M. Acoustica, 1993)\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book |title=[[A Guide to the Perplexed]] |translator= Philip Simpson |location=London|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]] |year=2002 |isbn=1-85242-826-0}}\n*''My one and only love''. London: Saqi Books, 2005. {{ISBN|0-86356-507-7}} (pbk.). {{ISBN|978-0-86356-507-6}} (pbk.)\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C| title=The Wandering Who?: A Study of Jewish Identity Politics |publisher=[[John Hunt Publishing|Zero Books]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-84694-875-6}}\n* ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon''. London, Fanfare Press, 2015.{{ISBN|978-0993183706}} (pbk.). \n*''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', Newbold on Stour, Warwickshire: Skyscraper Publications, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1911072201}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brian Lenzo, [http://www.palestinechronicle.com/old/view_article_details.php?id=16132 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed: Each Village is a Reminder], originally published by Socialist Worker Online, 13 July 2010 (reprinted by the Palestine Chronicle).\n*Alan Maass, [https://socialistworker.org/2010/07/14/an-article-retracted An Article Retracted], Socialist Worker Online, 14 July 2010 (retraction of preceding interview).\n*[http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/eveningnews24/norwich-whats-on-guide/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=GoingOutMusic&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=WhatsOn&itemid=NOED26%20Nov%202009%2016%3A03%3A06%3A953 Interview: Gilad Atzmon] by Rob Garratt, Evening News 24, 11 November 2009.\n*[https://archive.org/details/GiladAtzmonOnArabvoices.netJune2009 Gilad Atzmon interview on ArabVoices.net], [[KPFT]], June 2009 during visit to Houston, Texas.\n*Ivan Hewett, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3667959/Gilad-Altzmon-High-flown-ecstasies-from-an-angry-man.html Gilad Altzmon: High-flown ecstasies from an angry man], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 17 September 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133806/http://middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21321 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed by Mary Rizzo], Middle East Online, July 2007.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon website]\n\n{{The Blockheads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atzmon, Gilad}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:Anti-Judaism]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism]]\n[[Category:Bebop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:The Blockheads members]]\n[[Category:British jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:British male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Writers on Zionism]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCommentators", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gilad_Atzmon"}
{"title_page": "Francis Quirk", "text_new": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2017}}{{Original research|date=November 2017}}\n<!--\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Francis J. Quirk\n|image=\n|caption=Self-portrait\n}}\n-->\n\n'''Francis James Quirk''' (June 3, 1907 \u2013 February 5, 1974) was an American artist, educator, museum curator and TV personality. He is best known for his paintings of [[Edgar Lee Masters]] and [[Carl Sandburg|Carl Sandberg]], as well as his affiliation with [[Lehigh University]] as a professor and curator.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nFrancis Quirk was born on June 3, 1907 in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artprice.com/artist/193783/francis-joseph-quirk/biography|title=ArtPrice.com biography|website=ArtPrice.com}}</ref> His parents Edward and Anne (n\u00e9e O\u2019Neil) lived on 30 Waldo Street in Pawtucket, Rhode Island. He was the second of five children the others being an older brother Edward, a younger brother Henry, younger sister Anna M. and younger sister Helen M.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nQuirk completed his undergraduate work at the [[Rhode Island School of Design]] where he was the co-founder of a short-lived student humor publication, ''The Salamander''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.risd.edu/studentnewspapers_collection_thesalamander/|title=The Salamander (1925-1926) {{!}} Student Newspapers {{!}} Rhode Island School of Design|website=digitalcommons.risd.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> He completed his certificate in 1929 and his post graduate work in 1930. During this year he served on the staff of the \"Student Designer\" in the Art Department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.risd.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1018&context=studentnewspapers|title=The Student Designer (1930) {{!}} Student Newspapers {{!}} Rhode Island School of Design|website=digitalcommons.risd.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> He later continued post-graduate studies in 1941-1942 at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. Biographies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artprice.com/artist/193783/francis-joseph-quirk/biography|title=The biography of Francis Joseph QUIRK: information and auctions for the artworks by the artist Francis Joseph QUIRK - Artprice.com|last=EHRMANN|first=Thierry|website=www.artprice.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-15}}</ref> also list him as training in Provincetown, Massachusetts, Woodstock, New York, France and Italy.\n\n== Early years ==\nQuirk was an art teacher from 1930 until 1935 at the Montgomery School, for boys in grades 1-12 in [[Wynnewood, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/48470554/Our-Town-May-8-1931|title=Our Town May 8, 1931 {{!}} Foods {{!}} Leisure|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref> While teaching at the school, Quirk was quite active outside the classroom and establishing himself as a talented artist.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1932, Quirk successfully competed for a place at the [[The Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation|Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation]] that allowed him to spend three months at Tiffany's estate at [[Laurelton Hall]] in [[Cold Spring Harbor, New York|Cold Spring Harbor]] on Long Island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://louiscomforttiffanyfoundation.org/about.html|title=Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation|website=Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation}}</ref>  Judges for the competition included impressionist painter [[Childe Hassam|Child Hassam]] and sculptor [[Daniel Chester French]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/louis-comfort-tiffany-foundation-records-8562|title=Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation records, 1918-1968|website=www.aaa.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1932, Quirk exhibited at the [[Provincetown Art Association and Museum|Provincetown Art Association]] a painting of Fred Fischer's Place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.provincetownhistoryproject.com/PDF/059_276_578b-008-provincetown-art-association-exhibition-1932.pdf|title=Provincetown Art Association 1932 Exhibition Catalog|website=Provincetown History Project}}</ref> He also won the Juror's Prize at the [[Providence Art Club|Providence Art Club's]] Annual Exhibition with his painting of Scott Adams III.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/providence-art-club-records-5788|title=Archives of the Providence Art Club at The Archives of American Art}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://francisquirk.blogspot.com/2015/08/francis-j-quirk-wins-prize-at.html|title=Francis J. Quirk Wins Prize at Providence Art Club}}</ref>\n\n== Ogontz College ==\nIn 1935 Quirk began a 15-year relationship with the [[Penn State Abington|Ogontz School for Young Ladies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://libraries.psu.edu/about/collections/ogontz-school-1850-1950|title=The Ogontz School 1850-1950 {{!}} Penn State University Libraries|website=libraries.psu.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> For the first 5 years he was Professor of Art, Drawing, and Painting. For the last 10 years he was Head of the Art Department. While at Ogontz, on September 12, 1936, he married Anna F. Feeley with whom he had two children.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Anna also served on the faculty of Ogontz College.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} She also had artistic talent ability and later exhibited her paintings in Maine.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nQuirk was influential in mentoring at least one artist who rose to some level of prominence, [[Helen Bacon Hoffman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://francisquirk.blogspot.com/2016/02/helen-hoffman-another-artist-influenced.html|title=Francis Quirk Master Painter Blog Interview with Helen Hoffman|website=Francis Quirk Master Painter Blog}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at Ogontz, his reputation as a portrait painter grew considerably. He also painted [[Carl Sandburg]] at the request of Abby Sutherland Brown. The Writers Guild of Pennsylvania commissioned a portrait of [[Edgar Lee Masters]] in 1946 that later became the 70th painting to enter the collection of the US [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 1940, Quirk exhibited a painting of him and his wife attending a concert at the Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Art.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nTowards the end of Quirk's tenure at Ogontz he also was a Professor of Contemporary Perspective at Philadelphia's [[Hussian School of Art]]. He taught there from 1948-1950, shortly after the school's founding by John Hussian in 1946 with the support of principals at the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]].\n\n== Lehigh University ==\n1950 was a landmark year for Quirk as he made a major transition to the all-male [[Lehigh University]] where he took over from Garth Howland as in the Fine Art Department and Director of Exhibits. In his first year he would expand the exhibit space with the establishment of the Memorial Gallery. He would later win the University's [[Lindback Award|Lindbeck Award]] for distinguished teaching in 1965.\n\nAs Curator of the Collection he made three significant moves. First, he brought order through a comprehensive cataloging of the collection. Second, he created better display spaces and finally he began its expansion through donations from prominent alumni such as Ralph Wilson<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lehigh.edu/engineering/about/alumni/wilson.html|title=Ralph Wilson: Distinguished Alumni at Lehigh Engineering|website=www.lehigh.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> of the [[Timken Company]] and [[Eugene Grace]] of [[Bethlehem Steel]] and through borrowing. He also established lending relationships with the Ranger Fund, [[National Academy Museum and School|National Academy of Design]] and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. Quirk also ran numerous exhibitions and established a program for exhibiting student art.\n\nTechnically, Quirk was an excellent draftsman who worked in a variety of medium and styles. At the time, the art world was in revolution with modern movements such as cubism and abstract art emerging. Quirk experimented in cubism, but largely remained true to a realistic style of portraiture and marine subjects.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn the media, Quirk also hosted a television program Art as We See It, that was broadcast on [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]] Station, WGPA. He also appeared on Philadelphia's [[WFIL-TV|WFIL]] station program These our Own. {{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nDuring his time at Lehigh Quirk bought a home in the Mountain Club in [[Prescott, Arizona]]. He named the Pine Drive home ''Peterspen'' and was active in the Mountain Club community teaching art classes.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nQuirk retired from teaching in 1969, but remained affiliated with the school as professor emeritus through 1972 and had a solo show there in 1973. That show featured works from his time at the Ossabaw Island Foundation who had awarded him a grant in 1968 and a fellowship in 1972.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n== Retirement ==\nQuirk retired to Peterspen North, his home in the Kinney Shores area of [[Saco, Maine]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} He had spent many summers there and served as President of the Kinney Shores Association. He also exhibited his work at the Old Orchard Art Association where he had been honored with a prize in 1962 and sold his work through local galleries.  He died on February 5, 1974 in the National Medical Care center in Portland Maine. He was buried in the Laurel Hill Cemetery in Saco, Maine.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n== Awards and exhibitions ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2017}}\n* 1932, [[The Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation|Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation Fellowship]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 1940, Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Art\n* 1932, [[Providence Art Club]], Junior Prize\n*1946, Women's Club of Philadelphia, One Man Show<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Philadelphia Inquirer- Arts Section|date=February 16, 1946|work=Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 1950, Who's Who in the East Listing\n* 1950, Who's Who in Art\n* 1956, Ocean Park Judges Award\n* 1962, Old Orchard Award\n* 1965, [[Lindback Award]] for distinguished teaching [[Lehigh University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awards.web.lehigh.edu/node/658|title=Faculty Awards Lehigh University|last=|first=|date=|website=Awards Lehigh|access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n* Grantee 1968 and Fellow 1972, Ossabaw Island Project\n* 1970, Impossible Art Exhibition\n* 1973, Solo show, Allentown College of St. Francis de Sales\n* 1974, Solo show, Lehigh University Art Gallery\n\n== Collections ==\nNational Portrait Gallery, [[Snite Museum of Art]] ([[University of Notre Dame]]), Canton Art Institute, [[Georgia Museum of Art]], [[Colby College]] (President Strider), Lehigh University Art Galleries, Monroe County Medical Center, American Consulate Zurich, [[Wilson College (Pennsylvania)|Wilson College]], [[DeSales University|Allentown College]], Ships Museum (Savannah), Stroudsburg Hospital, Parker College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artprice.com/artist/193783/francis-joseph-quirk/biography|title=ArtPrice.com Biography|website=ArtPrice.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=October 1951|title=Man on the Cover Art Penetrates the Campus|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B7wmnR3K0c8XcENPVVJEaVAzV3c/view|journal=Lehigh Alumni Bulletin|volume=xxxix| issue = 1|pages=Cover, 8\u20139 19|via=}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quirk, Francis}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American curators]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:American portrait painters]]\n[[Category:American realist painters]]\n[[Category:American watercolorists]]\n[[Category:Painters from Maine]]\n[[Category:Painters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pastel artists]]\n[[Category:People from Lehigh County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Pawtucket, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:People from Saco, Maine]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2017}}{{Original research|date=November 2017}}\n<!--\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Francis J. Quirk\n|image=\n|caption=Self-portrait\n}}\n-->\n\n'''Francis James Quirk''' (June 3, 1907 \u2013 February 5, 1974) was an American artist, educator, museum curator and TV personality. He is best known for his paintings of [[Edgar Lee Masters]] and [[Carl Sandburg|Carl Sandberg]], as well as his affiliation with [[Lehigh University]] as a professor and curator.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nFrancis Quirk was born on June 3, 1907 in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artprice.com/artist/193783/francis-joseph-quirk/biography|title=ArtPrice.com biography|website=ArtPrice.com}}</ref> His parents Edward and Anne (n\u00e9e O\u2019Neil) lived on 30 Waldo Street in Pawtucket, Rhode Island. He was the second of five children the others being an older brother Edward, a younger brother Henry, younger sister Anna M. and younger sister Helen M.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nQuirk completed his undergraduate work at the [[Rhode Island School of Design]] where he was the co-founder of a short-lived student humor publication, ''The Salamander''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.risd.edu/studentnewspapers_collection_thesalamander/|title=The Salamander (1925-1926) {{!}} Student Newspapers {{!}} Rhode Island School of Design|website=digitalcommons.risd.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> He completed his certificate in 1929 and his post graduate work in 1930. During this year he served on the staff of the \"Student Designer\" in the Art Department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.risd.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1018&context=studentnewspapers|title=The Student Designer (1930) {{!}} Student Newspapers {{!}} Rhode Island School of Design|website=digitalcommons.risd.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> He later continued post-graduate studies in 1941-1942 at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. Biographies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artprice.com/artist/193783/francis-joseph-quirk/biography|title=The biography of Francis Joseph QUIRK: information and auctions for the artworks by the artist Francis Joseph QUIRK - Artprice.com|last=EHRMANN|first=Thierry|website=www.artprice.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-15}}</ref> also list him as training in Provincetown, Massachusetts, Woodstock, New York, France and Italy.\n\n== Early years ==\nQuirk was an art teacher from 1930 until 1935 at the Montgomery School, for boys in grades 1-12 in [[Wynnewood, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/48470554/Our-Town-May-8-1931|title=Our Town May 8, 1931 {{!}} Foods {{!}} Leisure|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref> While teaching at the school, Quirk was quite active outside the classroom and establishing himself as a talented artist.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1932, Quirk successfully competed for a place at the [[The Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation|Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation]] that allowed him to spend three months at Tiffany's estate at [[Laurelton Hall]] in [[Cold Spring Harbor, New York|Cold Spring Harbor]] on Long Island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://louiscomforttiffanyfoundation.org/about.html|title=Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation|website=Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation}}</ref>  Judges for the competition included impressionist painter [[Childe Hassam|Child Hassam]] and sculptor [[Daniel Chester French]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/louis-comfort-tiffany-foundation-records-8562|title=Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation records, 1918-1968|website=www.aaa.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1932, Quirk exhibited at the [[Provincetown Art Association and Museum|Provincetown Art Association]] a painting of Fred Fischer's Place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.provincetownhistoryproject.com/PDF/059_276_578b-008-provincetown-art-association-exhibition-1932.pdf|title=Provincetown Art Association 1932 Exhibition Catalog|website=Provincetown History Project}}</ref> He also won the Juror's Prize at the [[Providence Art Club|Providence Art Club's]] Annual Exhibition with his painting of Scott Adams III.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/providence-art-club-records-5788|title=Archives of the Providence Art Club at The Archives of American Art}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://francisquirk.blogspot.com/2015/08/francis-j-quirk-wins-prize-at.html|title=Francis J. Quirk Wins Prize at Providence Art Club}}</ref>\n\n== Ogontz College ==\nIn 1935 Quirk began a 15-year relationship with the [[Penn State Abington|Ogontz School for Young Ladies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://libraries.psu.edu/about/collections/ogontz-school-1850-1950|title=The Ogontz School 1850-1950 {{!}} Penn State University Libraries|website=libraries.psu.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> For the first 5 years he was Professor of Art, Drawing, and Painting. For the last 10 years he was Head of the Art Department. While at Ogontz, on September 12, 1936, he married Anna F. Feeley with whom he had two children.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Anna also served on the faculty of Ogontz College.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} She also had artistic talent ability and later exhibited her paintings in Maine.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nQuirk was influential in mentoring at least one artist who rose to some level of prominence, [[Helen Bacon Hoffman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://francisquirk.blogspot.com/2016/02/helen-hoffman-another-artist-influenced.html|title=Francis Quirk Master Painter Blog Interview with Helen Hoffman|website=Francis Quirk Master Painter Blog}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at Ogontz, his reputation as a portrait painter grew considerably. He also painted [[Carl Sandburg]] at the request of Abby Sutherland Brown. The Writers Guild of Pennsylvania commissioned a portrait of [[Edgar Lee Masters]] in 1946 that later became the 70th painting to enter the collection of the US [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 1940, Quirk exhibited a painting of him and his wife attending a concert at the Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Art.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nTowards the end of Quirk's tenure at Ogontz he also was a Professor of Contemporary Perspective at Philadelphia's [[Hussian School of Art]]. He taught there from 1948-1950, shortly after the school's founding by John Hussian in 1946 with the support of principals at the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]].\n\n== Lehigh University ==\n1950 was a landmark year for Quirk as he made a major transition to the all-male [[Lehigh University]] where he took over from Garth Howland as in the Fine Art Department and Director of Exhibits. In his first year he would expand the exhibit space with the establishment of the Memorial Gallery. He would later win the University's [[Lindback Award|Lindbeck Award]] for distinguished teaching in 1965.\n\nAs Curator of the Collection he made three significant moves. First, he brought order through a comprehensive cataloging of the collection. Second, he created better display spaces and finally he began its expansion through donations from prominent alumni such as Ralph Wilson<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lehigh.edu/engineering/about/alumni/wilson.html|title=Ralph Wilson: Distinguished Alumni at Lehigh Engineering|website=www.lehigh.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-25}}</ref> of the [[Timken Company]] and [[Eugene Grace]] of [[Bethlehem Steel]] and through borrowing. He also established lending relationships with the Ranger Fund, [[National Academy Museum and School|National Academy of Design]] and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. Quirk also ran numerous exhibitions and established a program for exhibiting student art.\n\nTechnically, Quirk was an excellent draftsman who worked in a variety of medium and styles. At the time, the art world was in revolution with modern movements such as cubism and abstract art emerging. Quirk experimented in cubism, but largely remained true to a realistic style of portraiture and marine subjects.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn the media, Quirk also hosted a television program Art as We See It, that was broadcast on [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]] Station, WGPA. He also appeared on Philadelphia's [[WFIL-TV|WFIL]] station program These our Own. {{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nDuring his time at Lehigh Quirk bought a home in the Mountain Club in [[Prescott, Arizona]]. He named the Pine Drive home ''Peterspen'' and was active in the Mountain Club community teaching art classes.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nQuirk retired from teaching in 1969, but remained affiliated with the school as professor emeritus through 1972 and had a solo show there in 1973. That show featured works from his time at the Ossabaw Island Foundation who had awarded him a grant in 1968 and a fellowship in 1972.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n== Retirement ==\nQuirk retired to Peterspen North, his home in the Kinney Shores area of [[Saco, Maine]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} He had spent many summers there and served as President of the Kinney Shores Association. He also exhibited his work at the Old Orchard Art Association where he had been honored with a prize in 1962 and sold his work through local galleries.  He died on February 5, 1974 in the National Medical Care center in Portland Maine. He was buried in the Laurel Hill Cemetery in Saco, Maine.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n== Awards and exhibitions ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2017}}\n* 1932, [[The Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation|Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation Fellowship]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 1940, Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Art\n* 1932, [[Providence Art Club]], Junior Prize\n* 1950, Who's Who in the East Listing\n* 1950, Who's Who in Art\n* 1956, Ocean Park Judges Award\n* 1962, Old Orchard Award\n* 1965, [[Lindback Award]] for distinguished teaching [[Lehigh University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awards.web.lehigh.edu/node/658|title=Faculty Awards Lehigh University|last=|first=|date=|website=Awards Lehigh|access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n* Grantee 1968 and Fellow 1972, Ossabaw Island Project\n* 1970, Impossible Art Exhibition\n* 1973, Solo show, Allentown College of St. Francis de Sales\n* 1974, Solo show, Lehigh University Art Gallery\n\n== Collections ==\nNational Portrait Gallery, [[Snite Museum of Art]] ([[University of Notre Dame]]), Canton Art Institute, [[Georgia Museum of Art]], [[Colby College]] (President Strider), Lehigh University Art Galleries, Monroe County Medical Center, American Consulate Zurich, [[Wilson College (Pennsylvania)|Wilson College]], [[DeSales University|Allentown College]], Ships Museum (Savannah), Stroudsburg Hospital, Parker College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artprice.com/artist/193783/francis-joseph-quirk/biography|title=ArtPrice.com Biography|website=ArtPrice.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=October 1951|title=Man on the Cover Art Penetrates the Campus|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B7wmnR3K0c8XcENPVVJEaVAzV3c/view|journal=Lehigh Alumni Bulletin|volume=xxxix| issue = 1|pages=Cover, 8\u20139 19|via=}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quirk, Francis}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American curators]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:American portrait painters]]\n[[Category:American realist painters]]\n[[Category:American watercolorists]]\n[[Category:Painters from Maine]]\n[[Category:Painters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pastel artists]]\n[[Category:People from Lehigh County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Pawtucket, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:People from Saco, Maine]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n", "name_user": "AndrewTJay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding in an exhibition", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Quirk"}
{"title_page": "Greek numerals", "text_new": "{{hatnote|The numerical signs \u02b9<!-- U+02B9 --> and \u0375 redirect here. For the accent mark ', see [[Acute accent]].}}\n{{numeral systems}}\n{{Special characters}}\n'''Greek numerals''', also known as '''Ionic''', '''Ionian''', '''Milesian''', or '''Alexandrian numerals''', are a [[numeral system|system of writing numbers]] using the letters of the [[Greek alphabet]]. In modern [[Greece]], they are still used for [[ordinal number (linguistics)|ordinal number]]s and in contexts similar to those in which [[Roman numerals]] are still used elsewhere in the West. For ordinary [[cardinal number (linguistics)|cardinal number]]s, however, Greece uses [[Arabic numerals]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Minoans|Minoan]] and [[Mycenaean civilization]]s' [[Linear A]] and [[Linear B]] alphabets used a different system, called [[Aegean numerals]], which included specialised symbols for numbers: {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd07}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1, {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd10}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10, {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd19}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;100, {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd22}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1000, and {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd2b}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10000.<ref name=Verdun>{{cite web|url=http://www.dma.ens.fr/culturemath/histoire%20des%20maths/htm/Verdan/Verdan.htm|title=Syst\u00e8mes num\u00e9raux en Gr\u00e8ce ancienne: description et mise en perspective historique|author=Samuel Verdan|date=20 March 2007 |accessdate=2 March 2011|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n[[Attic numerals]] was another system that came into use perhaps in the 7th century BC. They were [[acrophonic]], derived (after the initial one) from the first letters of the names of the numbers represented. They ran {{GrGl|Zeta archaic}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1, {{GrGl|Pi archaic}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;5, {{GrGl|Delta 04}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10, {{GrGl|Eta classical}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;100, {{GrGl|Chi normal}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1,000, and {{GrGl|Mu classical}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10,000. The numbers {{nowrap|50, 500, 5,000, and 50,000}} were represented by the letter {{GrGl|Pi archaic}} with minuscule powers of ten written in the top right corner: [[File:Attic_00050.svg|x16px]], [[File:Attic_00500.svg|x16px]], [[File:Attic_05000.svg|x16px]], and [[File:Attic_50000.svg|x16px]].<ref name=\"Verdun\" /> One-half was represented by \u2282 (left half of a full circle). The same system was used outside of [[Attica]], but the symbols varied with the [[Archaic Greek alphabets|local alphabets]]: in [[Boeotia]], {{GrGl|Psi_V-shaped}} was 1,000.<ref name=heman>Heath, Thomas L. ''A Manual of Greek Mathematics'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=_HZNr_mGFzQC&pg=PA14 pp. 14 ff.] Oxford Univ. Press (Oxford), 1931. Reprinted Dover ([[Mineola, New York|Mineola]]), 2003. Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref>\n\nThe present system probably developed around [[Miletus]] in [[Ionia]]. 19th-century classicists placed its development in the 3rd century BC, the occasion of its first widespread use.<ref>Thompson, Edward M. ''Handbook of Greek and Latin Palaeography'', p. 114. D. Appleton (New York), 1893.</ref> More thorough [[modern archaeology]] has caused the date to be pushed back at least to the 5th century BC,<ref>The Packard Humanities Institute (Cornell & Ohio State Universities). ''Searchable Greek Inscriptions'': \"[http://epigraphy.packhum.org/inscriptions/oi?ikey=1592&bookid=4&region=1 IG I<sup>3</sup> 1387]\" [also known as IG I<sup>2</sup> 760]. Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref> a little before [[Athens (city-state)|Athens]] abandoned its [[pre-Euclidean alphabet]] in favour of [[Ionic alphabet|Miletus]]'s in 402&nbsp;BC, and it may predate that by a century or two.<ref>Jeffery, Lilian H. ''The Local Scripts of Archaic Greece'', pp. 38 ff. Clarendon (Oxford), 1961.</ref> The present system uses the 24 letters adopted by [[Euclid]] as well as three [[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]] and Ionic ones that were not carried over: [[digamma (letter)|digamma]], [[koppa (letter)|koppa]], and [[sampi (letter)|sampi]]. The position of those characters within the numbering system imply that the first two were still in use (or at least remembered as letters) while the third was not. The exact dating, particularly for sampi, is problematic since its uncommon value means the first attested representative near Miletus does not appear until the 2nd century BC<ref>The Packard Humanities Institute (Cornell & Ohio State Universities). ''Searchable Greek Inscriptions'': \"[http://epigraphy.packhum.org/inscriptions/oi?ikey=260445&bookid=509&region=8&subregion=27 Magnesia 4]\" [also known as Syll\u00b3 695.b]. Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref> and its use is unattested in Athens until the 2nd century AD.<ref>The Packard Humanities Institute (Cornell & Ohio State Universities). ''Searchable Greek Inscriptions'': \"[http://epigraphy.packhum.org/inscriptions/oi?ikey=5028&bookid=5&region=1 IG II\u00b2 2776]\". Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref> (In general, Athens resisted the use of the new numerals for the longest of any of the Greek states but had fully adopted them by {{circa|lk=no|AD 50}}.<ref name=heman/>)\n\n==Description<!--linked from 'Keraia'-->==\n[[File:Greek minuscule numerals Cod.Const.Pal.Vet.f96r.svg|thumb|right|Greek numerals in a {{circa|lk=no|1100}} [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] manuscript of [[Hero of Alexandria]]'s ''Metrika''. The first line contains the number \"{{lang|grc|{{overline|\u0375\u03b8\u03e1\u03df\u03db}} \u03b4\u02b9 \u03db\u02b9}}\", i.e. \"{{nowrap|9,996 + {{frac|4}} + {{frac|6}}}}\". It features each of the special numeral symbols [[sampi]] (\u03e1), [[koppa (letter)|koppa]] (\u03df), and [[stigma (letter)|stigma]] (\u03db) in their [[Greek minuscule|minuscule]] forms.]]\n[[File:Add 19391 19-20.png|thumb|right|A 14th-century Byzantine map of the British Isles from a manuscript of [[Claudius Ptolemy|Ptolemy]]'s [[Ptolemy's Geography|''Geography'']], using Greek numerals for its [[Geographic coordinate system|graticule]]: 52\u201363\u00b0N of the [[equator]] and 6\u201333\u00b0E from Ptolemy's [[Prime Meridian]] at the [[Fortunate Isles]].]]\nGreek numerals are [[decimal]], based on powers of 10. The units from 1 to 9 are assigned to the first nine letters of the old [[Ionic alphabet]] from [[alpha (letter)|alpha]] to [[theta (letter)|theta]]. Instead of reusing these numbers to form multiples of the higher powers of ten, however, each multiple of ten from 10 to 90 was assigned its own separate letter from the next nine letters of the Ionic alphabet from [[iota (letter)|iota]] to [[koppa (letter)|koppa]]. Each multiple of one hundred from 100 to 900 was then assigned its own separate letter as well, from [[rho (letter)|rho]] to [[sampi (letter)|sampi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gwydir.demon.co.uk/jo/numbers/greek/|title=Classical Greek Numbers|last1=Edkins|first1=Jo|year=2006|accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> (The fact that this was ''not'' the traditional location of [[sampi (letter)|sampi]] or its possible predecessor [[san (letter)|san]] has led classicists to conclude that it was no longer in use even locally by the time the system was created.)\n\nThis [[alphabetic numeral system|alphabetic system]] operates on the additive principle in which the numeric values of the letters are added together to obtain the total. For example, 241 was represented as {{GrGl|Sigma classical}}{{GrGl|Mu classical}}{{GrGl|Alpha classical}}&nbsp;(200&nbsp;+&nbsp;40&nbsp;+&nbsp;1). (It was not always the case that the numbers ran from highest to lowest: a 4th-century BC inscription at Athens placed the units to the left of the tens. This practice continued in [[Asia Minor]] well into the [[Roman Greece|Roman period]].<ref name=heman/>) In ancient and medieval manuscripts, these numerals were eventually distinguished from letters using [[overbar]]s: {{overline|\u03b1}}, {{overline|\u03b2}}, {{overline|\u03b3}}, etc. In medieval manuscripts of the [[Book of Revelation]], the [[number of the Beast]] 666 is written as {{overline|\u03c7\u03be\u03db}}&nbsp;(600&nbsp;+&nbsp;60&nbsp;+&nbsp;6). (Numbers larger than 1,000 reused the same letters but included various marks to note the change.) Fractions were indicated as the denominator followed by a ''keraia'' (\u02b9);  \u03b3\u02b9 indicated one third, \u03b4\u02b9 one fourth and so on.  As an exception, special symbol \u2220\u02b9 indicated one half, and \u03b3\u00b0\u02b9 or \u03b3o\u02b9 was two-thirds.  These fractions were additive (also known as [[Egyptian fraction]]s); for example {{nowrap|\u03b4\u02b9 \u03db\u02b9}} indicated {{nowrap|{{frac|4}} + {{frac|6}} {{=}} {{frac|5|12}}}}.\n\nAlthough the [[Greek alphabet#Letter shapes|Greek alphabet]] began with only [[majuscule]] forms, surviving [[papyrus]] manuscripts from [[Roman Egypt|Egypt]] show that [[uncial]] and [[cursive]] [[Greek minuscule|minuscule]] forms began early.{{clarification|date=August 2017|reason=When? Minuscule was introduced in Constantinople not earlier than the first half of the 9th century, see Talk Uppercase/Lowercase}} These new letter forms sometimes replaced the former ones, especially in the case of the obscure numerals. The old Q-shaped koppa (\u03d8) began to be broken up ([[File:Greek Koppa cursive 02.svg|x16px]] and [[File:Greek Koppa cursive 03.svg|x16px]]) and simplified ([[File:Greek Koppa cursive 04.svg|x16px]] and [[File:Greek Koppa cursive 05.svg|x16px]]). The numeral for 6 changed several times. During antiquity, the original letter form of digamma (\u03dc) came to be avoided in favour of a special numerical one ({{GrGl|Digamma angular}}). By the [[Byzantine Greek|Byzantine era]], the letter was known as [[Digamma|episemon]] and written as {{GrGl|Digamma cursive 02}} or {{GrGl|Digamma cursive 06}}. This eventually merged with the [[sigma (letter)|sigma]]-[[tau (letter)|tau]] [[Typographic ligature|ligature]] [[stigma (letter)|stigma]] \u03db ({{GrGl|Digamma cursive 07}} or {{GrGl|Digamma cursive 04}}).\n\n{{anchor|keraia}}In [[modern Greek]], a number of other changes have been made. Instead of extending an over bar over an entire number, the '''''keraia'''''<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA--> ({{lang|el|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03af\u03b1}}, <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;\"hornlike projection\") is marked to its upper right, a development of the short marks formerly used for single numbers and fractions. The modern ''keraia'' is a symbol ({{keraia}}) similar to the [[acute accent]] (\u00b4), the [[tonos]] (U+0384,\u0384) and the prime symbol (U+02B9, \u02b9), but has its own [[Unicode]] character as U+0374. [[Alexander the Great]]'s father [[Philip II of Macedon]] is thus known as {{lang|el|\u03a6\u03af\u03bb\u03b9\u03c0\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u02b9}} in modern Greek. A lower left ''keraia'' (Unicode: U+0375, \"Greek Lower Numeral Sign\") is now standard for distinguishing thousands: 2019 is represented as \u0375\u0392\u0399\u0398\u02b9 ({{nowrap|2 \u00d7 1,000 + 10 + 9}}).\n\nThe declining use of ligatures in the 20th century also means that stigma is frequently written as the separate letters \u03a3\u03a4\u02b9, although a single ''keraia'' is used for the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tlg.uci.edu/~opoudjis/unicode/numerals.html|title=Numerals: Stigma, Koppa, Sampi|author=Nick Nicholas|date=9 April 2005|accessdate=2 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120805203248/http://www.tlg.uci.edu/~opoudjis/unicode/numerals.html|archivedate=2012-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==Isopsephy (Gematria)==\nThe art of assigning Greek letters also being thought of as numerals and therefore giving words, names and phrases a numeric sum that has meaning through being connected to words, names and phrases of similar sum is called [[isopsephy]] ([[gematria]]).\n\n==Table==\n{{anchor|Chart|List}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! |Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value !! !!Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value !! !!Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value !! !!Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Alpha classical}}||{{overline|\u03b1}}||{{lang|el|\u0391\u02b9}}||[[1 (number)|1]]\n|rowspan=9|\n|{{GrGl|Iota classical}}||{{overline|\u03b9}}||{{lang|el|\u0399\u02b9}}||[[10 (number)|10]]\n|rowspan=9|\n||{{GrGl|Rho classical}}||{{overline|\u03c1}}||{{lang|el|\u03a1\u02b9}}||[[100 (number)|100]]\n|rowspan=9|\n||{{GrGl|Sampi 1000}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi 1000 (2)}}||\u0375\u03b1||,\u0391||[[1000 (number)|1000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Beta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b2}}||{{lang|el|\u0392\u02b9}}||[[2 (number)|2]]||{{GrGl|Kappa classical}}||{{overline|\u03ba}}||{{lang|el|\u039a\u02b9}}||[[20 (number)|20]]||{{GrGl|Sigma classical}}||{{overline|\u03c3}}||{{lang|el|\u03a3\u02b9}}||[[200 (number)|200]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Beta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b2||,\u0392||[[2000 (number)|2000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Gamma classical}}||{{overline|\u03b3}}||{{lang|el|\u0393\u02b9}}||[[3 (number)|3]]||{{GrGl|Lambda classical}}||{{overline|\u03bb}}||{{lang|el|\u039b\u02b9}}||[[30 (number)|30]]||{{GrGl|Tau classical}}||{{overline|\u03c4}}||\u03a4\u02b9||[[300 (number)|300]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Gamma_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375{{GrGl|Gamma 02}}||,\u0393||[[3000 (number)|3000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Delta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b4}}||{{lang|el|\u0394\u02b9}}||[[4 (number)|4]]||{{GrGl|Mu classical}}||{{overline|\u03bc}}||{{lang|el|\u039c\u02b9}}||[[40 (number)|40]]||{{GrGl|Upsilon classical}}||{{overline|\u03c5}}||{{lang|el|\u03a5\u02b9}}||[[400 (number)|400]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Delta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375{{GrGl|Delta classical}}||,\u0394||[[4000 (number)|4000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Epsilon classical}}||{{overline|\u03b5}}||{{lang|el|\u0395\u02b9}}||[[5 (number)|5]]||{{GrGl|Nu classical}}||{{overline|\u03bd}}||{{lang|el|\u039d\u02b9}}||[[50 (number)|50]]||{{GrGl|Phi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c6}}||{{lang|el|\u03a6\u02b9}}||[[500 (number)|500]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Epsilon_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b5||,\u0395||[[5000 (number)|5000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Digamma oblique}}<br>{{GrGl|Digamma angular}}||{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 02}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 04}}<br>{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 06}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 07}}||{{lang|el|\u03da\u02b9}}<br>\u03dc\u02b9||[[6 (number)|6]]||{{GrGl|Xi classical}}||{{overline|\u03be}}||\u039e\u02b9||[[60 (number)|60]]||{{GrGl|Chi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c7}}||{{lang|el|\u03a7\u02b9}}||[[600 (number)|600]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Digamma_angular.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 02}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 04}}<br>\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 06}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 07}}||,\u03dc<br>||[[6000 (number)|6000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Zeta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b6}}||{{lang|el|\u0396\u02b9}}||[[7 (number)|7]]||{{GrGl|Omicron classical}}||{{overline|\u03bf}}||{{lang|el|\u039f\u02b9}}||[[70 (number)|70]]||{{GrGl|Psi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c8}}||{{lang|el|\u03a8\u02b9}}||[[700 (number)|700]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Zeta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b6||,\u0396||[[7000 (number)|7000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Eta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b7}}||{{lang|el|\u0397\u02b9}}||[[8 (number)|8]]||{{GrGl|Pi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c0}}||{{lang|el|\u03a0\u02b9}}||[[80 (number)|80]]||{{GrGl|Omega classical}}||{{overline|\u03c9}}||{{lang|el|\u03a9\u02b9}}||[[800 (number)|800]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Eta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b7||,\u0397||[[8000 (number)|8000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Theta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b8}}||{{lang|el|\u0398\u02b9}}||[[9 (number)|9]]||{{GrGl|Koppa normal}}<br>{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 01}}||{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 02}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 04}}<br>{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 03}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 05}}||\u03d8\u02b9||[[90 (number)|90]]||{{GrGl|Sampi Ionian}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 05}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 15}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 06}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 09}}||{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 03}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 07}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 08}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 10}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 11}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 14}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 13}}<br>[[File:Sampi.svg|x16px]]||\u0372\u02b9||[[900 (number)|900]]||{{GrGl|Sampi 9000}}||\u0375\u03b8||,\u0398||[[9000 (number)|9000]]\n|}\n* Alternatively, sub-sections of manuscripts are sometimes numbered by [[Greek alphabet#Letter shapes|lowercase characters]] (\u03b1\u02b9. \u03b2\u02b9. \u03b3\u02b9. \u03b4\u02b9. \u03b5\u02b9. \u03db\u02b9. \u03b6\u02b9. \u03b7\u02b9. \u03b8\u02b9.).\n* In Ancient Greek, [[myriad]] notation is used for multiples of 10,000, for example {{overset|\u03b2|\u039c}} for 20,000 or {{overset|\u03c1\u03ba\u03b3|\u039c}}{{overline|\u0375\u03b4\u03c6\u03be\u03b6}} (also written on the line as {{overline|\u03c1\u03ba\u03b3}}\u039c&nbsp;{{overline|\u0375\u03b4\u03c6\u03be\u03b6}}) for 1,234,567.<ref name=mactutor>[http://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/PrintHT/Greek_numbers.html Greek number systems - MacTutor]</ref>\n\n==Higher numbers==\nIn his text ''[[The Sand Reckoner]]'', the natural philosopher [[Archimedes]] gives an upper bound of the number of grains of sand required to fill the entire universe, using a contemporary estimation of its size.  This would defy the then-held notion that it is impossible to name a number greater than that of the sand on a beach or on the entire world.  In order to do that, he had to devise a [[The Sand Reckoner#Naming large numbers|new numeral scheme]] with much greater range.\n\n[[Pappus of Alexandria]] reports that [[Apollonius of Perga]] developed a simpler system based on [[Exponentiation|powers]] of the myriad; {{overset|\u03b1|\u039c}} was 10,000, {{overset|\u03b2|\u039c}} was 10,000<sup>2</sup> = 100,000,000, {{overset|\u03b3|\u039c}} was 10,000<sup>3</sup> = 10<sup>12</sup> and so on.<ref name=mactutor/>\n\n==Zero==\n[[File:P. Lund, Inv. 35a.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Example of the early Greek symbol for zero (lower right corner) from a 2nd-century papyrus]]\n{{anchor|Hellenistic zero}}<!--linked from \"Number\"-->\n[[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenistic]] [[astronomer]]s extended alphabetic Greek numerals into a [[sexagesimal]] [[positional notation|positional]] [[numeral system|numbering system]] by limiting each position to a maximum value of 50&nbsp;+&nbsp;9 and including a special symbol for [[0 (number)|zero]], which was also used alone like today's modern zero, more than as a simple placeholder. However, the positions were usually limited to the fractional part of a number (called minutes, seconds, thirds, fourths, etc.) \u2014 they were not used for the [[integer|integral]] part of a number. This system was probably adapted from [[Babylonian numerals]] by [[Hipparchus]] {{circa|140 BC}}. It was then used by [[Ptolemy]] ({{circa|140}}), [[Theon of Alexandria|Theon]] ({{circa|380}}) and Theon's daughter [[Hypatia of Alexandria|Hypatia]] (died&nbsp;415).\n\nIn [[Ptolemy's table of chords]], the first fairly extensive trigonometric table, there were 360 rows, portions of which looked as follows:\n\n: <math>\n\\begin{array}{ccc} \\pi\\varepsilon\\varrho\\iota\\varphi\\varepsilon\\varrho\\varepsilon\\iota\\tilde\\omega\\nu & \\overset{\\text{'}}\\varepsilon\\nu\\vartheta\\varepsilon\\iota\\tilde\\omega\\nu & \\overset{\\text{`}}\\varepsilon\\xi\\eta\\kappa\\omicron\\sigma\\tau\\tilde\\omega\\nu \\\\\n\\begin{array}{|l|} \\hline \\pi\\delta\\angle' \\\\  \\pi\\varepsilon \\\\  \\pi\\varepsilon\\angle' \\\\  \\hline  \\pi\\stigma \\\\  \\pi\\stigma\\angle' \\\\  \\pi\\zeta \\\\  \\hline \\end{array} & \\begin{array}{|r|r|r|} \\hline \\pi & \\mu\\alpha & \\gamma \\\\  \\pi\\alpha & \\delta & \\iota\\varepsilon \\\\  \\pi\\alpha & \\kappa\\zeta & \\kappa\\beta \\\\  \\hline \\pi\\alpha & \\nu & \\kappa\\delta \\\\  \\pi\\beta & \\iota\\gamma & \\iota\\vartheta \\\\  \\pi\\beta & \\lambda\\stigma & \\vartheta \\\\  \\hline \\end{array} & \\begin{array}{|r|r|r|r|} \\hline \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\stigma & \\kappa\\varepsilon \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\stigma & \\iota\\delta \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\stigma & \\gamma \\\\  \\hline \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\varepsilon & \\nu\\beta \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\varepsilon & \\mu \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\varepsilon & \\kappa\\vartheta \\\\  \\hline \\end{array}\n\\end{array}\n</math>\nEach number in the first column, labeled {{lang|grc|\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u1ff6\u03bd}}, is the number of degrees of arc on a circle.  Each number in the second column, labeled {{lang|grc|\u03b5\u1f50\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u1ff6\u03bd}}, is the length of the corresponding chord of the circle, when the diameter is 120.  Thus \u03c0\u03b4 represents an 84\u00b0 arc, and the \u2220\u2032 after it means one-half, so that \u03c0\u03b4\u2220\u2032 means {{frac|84|1|2}}\u00b0.  In the next column we see \u03c0&nbsp;\u03bc\u03b1&nbsp;\u03b3, meaning 80&nbsp;+&nbsp;{{sfrac|41|60}}&nbsp;+&nbsp;{{sfrac|3|60<sup>2</sup>}}.  That is the length of the chord corresponding to an arc of {{frac|84|1|2}}\u00b0 when the diameter of the circle is&nbsp;120.  The next column, labeled {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03be\u03b7\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u1ff6\u03bd}}, for \"sixtieths\", is the number to be added to the chord length for each 1\u00b0 increase in the arc, over the span of the next 12\u00b0.  Thus that last column was used for [[linear interpolation]].\n\nThe Greek sexagesimal placeholder or zero symbol changed over time. The symbol used on [[papyrus|papyri]] during the second century was a very small circle with an overbar several diameters long, terminated or not at both ends in various ways. Later, the overbar shortened to only one diameter, similar to the modern ''o'' macron (\u014d) which was still being used in late medieval Arabic manuscripts whenever alphabetic numerals were used. But the overbar was omitted in [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] manuscripts, leaving a bare ''\u03bf'' (omicron). This gradual change from an invented symbol to ''\u03bf'' does not support the hypothesis that the latter was the initial of \u03bf\u1f50\u03b4\u03ad\u03bd meaning \"nothing\".<ref>{{Cite book | edition = 2 | publisher = [[Dover Publications]] | last = Neugebauer | first = Otto | author-link = Otto E. Neugebauer | title = The Exact Sciences in Antiquity | origyear = 1957 | year = 1969 | isbn = 978-0-486-22332-2 | pages = 13\u201314, plate 2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Raymond |last=Mercier|url= http://www.raymondm.co.uk/prog/GreekZeroSign.pdf |title=Consideration of the Greek symbol 'zero' }} Numerous examples</ref> Note that the letter ''\u03bf'' was still used with its original numerical value of 70; however, there was no ambiguity, as 70 could not appear in the fractional part of a number, and zero was usually omitted when it was the integer.\n\nSome of Ptolemy's true zeros appeared in the first line of each of his eclipse tables, where they were a measure of the angular separation between the center of the [[Moon]] and either the center of the [[Sun]] (for [[solar eclipse]]s) or the center of [[Earth]]'s shadow (for [[lunar eclipse]]s). All of these zeros took the form {{nowrap|\u03bf {{!}} \u03bf \u03bf}}, where Ptolemy actually used three of the symbols described in the previous paragraph. The vertical bar (|) indicates that the integral part on the left was in a separate column labeled in the headings of his tables as ''digits'' (of five arc-minutes each), whereas the fractional part was in the next column labeled ''minute of immersion'', meaning sixtieths (and thirty-six-hundredths) of a digit.<ref>''Ptolemy's [[Almagest]]'', translated by [[G. J. Toomer]], Book VI, (Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press, 1998), pp.&nbsp;306\u20137.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Attic numerals]]\n*[[Cyrillic numerals]]\n*[[Gematria]]\n*[[Unicode numerals#Ancient Greek numerals|Greek numerals in Unicode]] (acrophonic, not alphabetic, numerals)\n*[[Isopsephy]]\n*[[Number of the Beast]]\n*[[Alphabetic numeral system]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Greek numerals}}\n* [http://www.russellcottrell.com/greek/utilities/GreekNumberConverter.htm The Greek Number Converter]\n\n{{Greek language}}\n{{Ancient Greece topics}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greek Numerals}}\n[[Category:Numeral systems]]\n[[Category:Numerals]]\n[[Category:Greek mathematics|Numerals]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|The numerical signs \u02b9<!-- U+02B9 --> and \u0375 redirect here. For the accent mark ', see [[Acute accent]].}}\n{{numeral systems}}\n{{Special characters}}\n'''Greek numerals''', also known as '''Ionic''', '''Ionian''', '''Milesian''', or '''Alexandrian numerals''', are a [[numeral system|system of writing numbers]] using the letters of the [[Greek alphabet]]. In modern [[Greece]], they are still used for [[ordinal number (linguistics)|ordinal number]]s and in contexts similar to those in which [[Roman numerals]] are still used elsewhere in the West. For ordinary [[cardinal number (linguistics)|cardinal number]]s, however, Greece uses [[Arabic numerals]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Minoans|Minoan]] and [[Mycenaean civilization]]s' [[Linear A]] and [[Linear B]] alphabets used a different system, called [[Aegean numerals]], which included specialised symbols for numbers: {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd07}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1, {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd10}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10, {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd19}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;100, {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd22}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1000, and {{lang|gmy|\ud800\udd2b}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10000.<ref name=Verdun>{{cite web|url=http://www.dma.ens.fr/culturemath/histoire%20des%20maths/htm/Verdan/Verdan.htm|title=Syst\u00e8mes num\u00e9raux en Gr\u00e8ce ancienne: description et mise en perspective historique|author=Samuel Verdan|date=20 March 2007 |accessdate=2 March 2011|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n[[Attic numerals]] was another system that came into use perhaps in the 7th century BC. They were [[acrophonic]], derived (after the initial one) from the first letters of the names of the numbers represented. They ran {{GrGl|Zeta archaic}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1, {{GrGl|Pi archaic}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;5, {{GrGl|Delta 04}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10, {{GrGl|Eta classical}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;100, {{GrGl|Chi normal}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;1,000, and {{GrGl|Mu classical}}&nbsp;=&nbsp;10,000. The numbers {{nowrap|50, 500, 5,000, and 50,000}} were represented by the letter {{GrGl|Pi archaic}} with minuscule powers of ten written in the top right corner: [[File:Attic_00050.svg|x16px]], [[File:Attic_00500.svg|x16px]], [[File:Attic_05000.svg|x16px]], and [[File:Attic_50000.svg|x16px]].<ref name=\"Verdun\" /> One-half was represented by \u2282 (left half of a full circle). The same system was used outside of [[Attica]], but the symbols varied with the [[Archaic Greek alphabets|local alphabets]]: in [[Boeotia]], {{GrGl|Psi_V-shaped}} was 1,000.<ref name=heman>Heath, Thomas L. ''A Manual of Greek Mathematics'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=_HZNr_mGFzQC&pg=PA14 pp. 14 ff.] Oxford Univ. Press (Oxford), 1931. Reprinted Dover ([[Mineola, New York|Mineola]]), 2003. Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref>\n\nThe present system probably developed around [[Miletus]] in [[Ionia]]. 19th-century classicists placed its development in the 3rd century BC, the occasion of its first widespread use.<ref>Thompson, Edward M. ''Handbook of Greek and Latin Palaeography'', p. 114. D. Appleton (New York), 1893.</ref> More thorough [[modern archaeology]] has caused the date to be pushed back at least to the 5th century BC,<ref>The Packard Humanities Institute (Cornell & Ohio State Universities). ''Searchable Greek Inscriptions'': \"[http://epigraphy.packhum.org/inscriptions/oi?ikey=1592&bookid=4&region=1 IG I<sup>3</sup> 1387]\" [also known as IG I<sup>2</sup> 760]. Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref> a little before [[Athens (city-state)|Athens]] abandoned its [[pre-Euclidean alphabet]] in favour of [[Ionic alphabet|Miletus]]'s in 402&nbsp;BC, and it may predate that by a century or two.<ref>Jeffery, Lilian H. ''The Local Scripts of Archaic Greece'', pp. 38 ff. Clarendon (Oxford), 1961.</ref> The present system uses the 24 letters adopted by [[Euclid]] as well as three [[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]] and Ionic ones that were not carried over: [[digamma (letter)|digamma]], [[koppa (letter)|koppa]], and [[sampi (letter)|sampi]]. The position of those characters within the numbering system imply that the first two were still in use (or at least remembered as letters) while the third was not. The exact dating, particularly for sampi, is problematic since its uncommon value means the first attested representative near Miletus does not appear until the 2nd century BC<ref>The Packard Humanities Institute (Cornell & Ohio State Universities). ''Searchable Greek Inscriptions'': \"[http://epigraphy.packhum.org/inscriptions/oi?ikey=260445&bookid=509&region=8&subregion=27 Magnesia 4]\" [also known as Syll\u00b3 695.b]. Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref> and its use is unattested in Athens until the 2nd century AD.<ref>The Packard Humanities Institute (Cornell & Ohio State Universities). ''Searchable Greek Inscriptions'': \"[http://epigraphy.packhum.org/inscriptions/oi?ikey=5028&bookid=5&region=1 IG II\u00b2 2776]\". Accessed 1 November 2013.</ref> (In general, Athens resisted the use of the new numerals for the longest of any of the Greek states but had fully adopted them by {{circa|lk=no|AD 50}}.<ref name=heman/>)\u2264\u2265\n\n==Description<!--linked from 'Keraia'-->==\n[[File:Greek minuscule numerals Cod.Const.Pal.Vet.f96r.svg|thumb|right|Greek numerals in a {{circa|lk=no|1100}} [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] manuscript of [[Hero of Alexandria]]'s ''Metrika''. The first line contains the number \"{{lang|grc|{{overline|\u0375\u03b8\u03e1\u03df\u03db}} \u03b4\u02b9 \u03db\u02b9}}\", i.e. \"{{nowrap|9,996 + {{frac|4}} + {{frac|6}}}}\". It features each of the special numeral symbols [[sampi]] (\u03e1), [[koppa (letter)|koppa]] (\u03df), and [[stigma (letter)|stigma]] (\u03db) in their [[Greek minuscule|minuscule]] forms.]]\n[[File:Add 19391 19-20.png|thumb|right|A 14th-century Byzantine map of the British Isles from a manuscript of [[Claudius Ptolemy|Ptolemy]]'s [[Ptolemy's Geography|''Geography'']], using Greek numerals for its [[Geographic coordinate system|graticule]]: 52\u201363\u00b0N of the [[equator]] and 6\u201333\u00b0E from Ptolemy's [[Prime Meridian]] at the [[Fortunate Isles]].]]\nGreek numerals are [[decimal]], based on powers of 10. The units from 1 to 9 are assigned to the first nine letters of the old [[Ionic alphabet]] from [[alpha (letter)|alpha]] to [[theta (letter)|theta]]. Instead of reusing these numbers to form multiples of the higher powers of ten, however, each multiple of ten from 10 to 90 was assigned its own separate letter from the next nine letters of the Ionic alphabet from [[iota (letter)|iota]] to [[koppa (letter)|koppa]]. Each multiple of one hundred from 100 to 900 was then assigned its own separate letter as well, from [[rho (letter)|rho]] to [[sampi (letter)|sampi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gwydir.demon.co.uk/jo/numbers/greek/|title=Classical Greek Numbers|last1=Edkins|first1=Jo|year=2006|accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> (The fact that this was ''not'' the traditional location of [[sampi (letter)|sampi]] or its possible predecessor [[san (letter)|san]] has led classicists to conclude that it was no longer in use even locally by the time the system was created.)\n\nThis [[alphabetic numeral system|alphabetic system]] operates on the additive principle in which the numeric values of the letters are added together to obtain the total. For example, 241 was represented as {{GrGl|Sigma classical}}{{GrGl|Mu classical}}{{GrGl|Alpha classical}}&nbsp;(200&nbsp;+&nbsp;40&nbsp;+&nbsp;1). (It was not always the case that the numbers ran from highest to lowest: a 4th-century BC inscription at Athens placed the units to the left of the tens. This practice continued in [[Asia Minor]] well into the [[Roman Greece|Roman period]].<ref name=heman/>) In ancient and medieval manuscripts, these numerals were eventually distinguished from letters using [[overbar]]s: {{overline|\u03b1}}, {{overline|\u03b2}}, {{overline|\u03b3}}, etc. In medieval manuscripts of the [[Book of Revelation]], the [[number of the Beast]] 666 is written as {{overline|\u03c7\u03be\u03db}}&nbsp;(600&nbsp;+&nbsp;60&nbsp;+&nbsp;6). (Numbers larger than 1,000 reused the same letters but included various marks to note the change.) Fractions were indicated as the denominator followed by a ''keraia'' (\u02b9);  \u03b3\u02b9 indicated one third, \u03b4\u02b9 one fourth and so on.  As an exception, special symbol \u2220\u02b9 indicated one half, and \u03b3\u00b0\u02b9 or \u03b3o\u02b9 was two-thirds.  These fractions were additive (also known as [[Egyptian fraction]]s); for example {{nowrap|\u03b4\u02b9 \u03db\u02b9}} indicated {{nowrap|{{frac|4}} + {{frac|6}} {{=}} {{frac|5|12}}}}.\n\nAlthough the [[Greek alphabet#Letter shapes|Greek alphabet]] began with only [[majuscule]] forms, surviving [[papyrus]] manuscripts from [[Roman Egypt|Egypt]] show that [[uncial]] and [[cursive]] [[Greek minuscule|minuscule]] forms began early.{{clarification|date=August 2017|reason=When? Minuscule was introduced in Constantinople not earlier than the first half of the 9th century, see Talk Uppercase/Lowercase}} These new letter forms sometimes replaced the former ones, especially in the case of the obscure numerals. The old Q-shaped koppa (\u03d8) began to be broken up ([[File:Greek Koppa cursive 02.svg|x16px]] and [[File:Greek Koppa cursive 03.svg|x16px]]) and simplified ([[File:Greek Koppa cursive 04.svg|x16px]] and [[File:Greek Koppa cursive 05.svg|x16px]]). The numeral for 6 changed several times. During antiquity, the original letter form of digamma (\u03dc) came to be avoided in favour of a special numerical one ({{GrGl|Digamma angular}}). By the [[Byzantine Greek|Byzantine era]], the letter was known as [[Digamma|episemon]] and written as {{GrGl|Digamma cursive 02}} or {{GrGl|Digamma cursive 06}}. This eventually merged with the [[sigma (letter)|sigma]]-[[tau (letter)|tau]] [[Typographic ligature|ligature]] [[stigma (letter)|stigma]] \u03db ({{GrGl|Digamma cursive 07}} or {{GrGl|Digamma cursive 04}}).\n\n{{anchor|keraia}}In [[modern Greek]], a number of other changes have been made. Instead of extending an over bar over an entire number, the '''''keraia'''''<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA--> ({{lang|el|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03af\u03b1}}, <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;\"hornlike projection\") is marked to its upper right, a development of the short marks formerly used for single numbers and fractions. The modern ''keraia'' is a symbol ({{keraia}}) similar to the [[acute accent]] (\u00b4), the [[tonos]] (U+0384,\u0384) and the prime symbol (U+02B9, \u02b9), but has its own [[Unicode]] character as U+0374. [[Alexander the Great]]'s father [[Philip II of Macedon]] is thus known as {{lang|el|\u03a6\u03af\u03bb\u03b9\u03c0\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u02b9}} in modern Greek. A lower left ''keraia'' (Unicode: U+0375, \"Greek Lower Numeral Sign\") is now standard for distinguishing thousands: 2019 is represented as \u0375\u0392\u0399\u0398\u02b9 ({{nowrap|2 \u00d7 1,000 + 10 + 9}}).\n\nThe declining use of ligatures in the 20th century also means that stigma is frequently written as the separate letters \u03a3\u03a4\u02b9, although a single ''keraia'' is used for the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tlg.uci.edu/~opoudjis/unicode/numerals.html|title=Numerals: Stigma, Koppa, Sampi|author=Nick Nicholas|date=9 April 2005|accessdate=2 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120805203248/http://www.tlg.uci.edu/~opoudjis/unicode/numerals.html|archivedate=2012-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==Isopsephy (Gematria)==\nThe art of assigning Greek letters also being thought of as numerals and therefore giving words, names and phrases a numeric sum that has meaning through being connected to words, names and phrases of similar sum is called [[isopsephy]] ([[gematria]]).\n\n==Table==\n{{anchor|Chart|List}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! |Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value !! !!Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value !! !!Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value !! !!Ancient!!Byzantine!!Modern!!Value\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Alpha classical}}||{{overline|\u03b1}}||{{lang|el|\u0391\u02b9}}||[[1 (number)|1]]\n|rowspan=9|\n|{{GrGl|Iota classical}}||{{overline|\u03b9}}||{{lang|el|\u0399\u02b9}}||[[10 (number)|10]]\n|rowspan=9|\n||{{GrGl|Rho classical}}||{{overline|\u03c1}}||{{lang|el|\u03a1\u02b9}}||[[100 (number)|100]]\n|rowspan=9|\n||{{GrGl|Sampi 1000}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi 1000 (2)}}||\u0375\u03b1||,\u0391||[[1000 (number)|1000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Beta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b2}}||{{lang|el|\u0392\u02b9}}||[[2 (number)|2]]||{{GrGl|Kappa classical}}||{{overline|\u03ba}}||{{lang|el|\u039a\u02b9}}||[[20 (number)|20]]||{{GrGl|Sigma classical}}||{{overline|\u03c3}}||{{lang|el|\u03a3\u02b9}}||[[200 (number)|200]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Beta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b2||,\u0392||[[2000 (number)|2000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Gamma classical}}||{{overline|\u03b3}}||{{lang|el|\u0393\u02b9}}||[[3 (number)|3]]||{{GrGl|Lambda classical}}||{{overline|\u03bb}}||{{lang|el|\u039b\u02b9}}||[[30 (number)|30]]||{{GrGl|Tau classical}}||{{overline|\u03c4}}||\u03a4\u02b9||[[300 (number)|300]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Gamma_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375{{GrGl|Gamma 02}}||,\u0393||[[3000 (number)|3000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Delta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b4}}||{{lang|el|\u0394\u02b9}}||[[4 (number)|4]]||{{GrGl|Mu classical}}||{{overline|\u03bc}}||{{lang|el|\u039c\u02b9}}||[[40 (number)|40]]||{{GrGl|Upsilon classical}}||{{overline|\u03c5}}||{{lang|el|\u03a5\u02b9}}||[[400 (number)|400]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Delta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375{{GrGl|Delta classical}}||,\u0394||[[4000 (number)|4000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Epsilon classical}}||{{overline|\u03b5}}||{{lang|el|\u0395\u02b9}}||[[5 (number)|5]]||{{GrGl|Nu classical}}||{{overline|\u03bd}}||{{lang|el|\u039d\u02b9}}||[[50 (number)|50]]||{{GrGl|Phi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c6}}||{{lang|el|\u03a6\u02b9}}||[[500 (number)|500]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Epsilon_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b5||,\u0395||[[5000 (number)|5000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Digamma oblique}}<br>{{GrGl|Digamma angular}}||{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 02}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 04}}<br>{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 06}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 07}}||{{lang|el|\u03da\u02b9}}<br>\u03dc\u02b9||[[6 (number)|6]]||{{GrGl|Xi classical}}||{{overline|\u03be}}||\u039e\u02b9||[[60 (number)|60]]||{{GrGl|Chi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c7}}||{{lang|el|\u03a7\u02b9}}||[[600 (number)|600]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Digamma_angular.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 02}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 04}}<br>\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 06}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;\u0375{{GrGl|Digamma cursive 07}}||,\u03dc<br>||[[6000 (number)|6000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Zeta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b6}}||{{lang|el|\u0396\u02b9}}||[[7 (number)|7]]||{{GrGl|Omicron classical}}||{{overline|\u03bf}}||{{lang|el|\u039f\u02b9}}||[[70 (number)|70]]||{{GrGl|Psi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c8}}||{{lang|el|\u03a8\u02b9}}||[[700 (number)|700]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Zeta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b6||,\u0396||[[7000 (number)|7000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Eta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b7}}||{{lang|el|\u0397\u02b9}}||[[8 (number)|8]]||{{GrGl|Pi classical}}||{{overline|\u03c0}}||{{lang|el|\u03a0\u02b9}}||[[80 (number)|80]]||{{GrGl|Omega classical}}||{{overline|\u03c9}}||{{lang|el|\u03a9\u02b9}}||[[800 (number)|800]]||<sup>[[File:Greek_Eta_classical.svg|x8px]]</sup><sub>[[File:Greek_Sampi_palaeographic_02.svg|x16px]]</sub>||\u0375\u03b7||,\u0397||[[8000 (number)|8000]]\n|-\n|{{GrGl|Theta classical}}||{{overline|\u03b8}}||{{lang|el|\u0398\u02b9}}||[[9 (number)|9]]||{{GrGl|Koppa normal}}<br>{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 01}}||{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 02}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 04}}<br>{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 03}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Koppa cursive 05}}||\u03d8\u02b9||[[90 (number)|90]]||{{GrGl|Sampi Ionian}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 05}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 15}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 06}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 09}}||{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 03}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 07}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 08}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 10}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 11}}<br>{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 14}}&nbsp;and&nbsp;{{GrGl|Sampi palaeographic 13}}<br>[[File:Sampi.svg|x16px]]||\u0372\u02b9||[[900 (number)|900]]||{{GrGl|Sampi 9000}}||\u0375\u03b8||,\u0398||[[9000 (number)|9000]]\n|}\n* Alternatively, sub-sections of manuscripts are sometimes numbered by [[Greek alphabet#Letter shapes|lowercase characters]] (\u03b1\u02b9. \u03b2\u02b9. \u03b3\u02b9. \u03b4\u02b9. \u03b5\u02b9. \u03db\u02b9. \u03b6\u02b9. \u03b7\u02b9. \u03b8\u02b9.).\n* In Ancient Greek, [[myriad]] notation is used for multiples of 10,000, for example {{overset|\u03b2|\u039c}} for 20,000 or {{overset|\u03c1\u03ba\u03b3|\u039c}}{{overline|\u0375\u03b4\u03c6\u03be\u03b6}} (also written on the line as {{overline|\u03c1\u03ba\u03b3}}\u039c&nbsp;{{overline|\u0375\u03b4\u03c6\u03be\u03b6}}) for 1,234,567.<ref name=mactutor>[http://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/PrintHT/Greek_numbers.html Greek number systems - MacTutor]</ref>\n\n==Higher numbers==\nIn his text ''[[The Sand Reckoner]]'', the natural philosopher [[Archimedes]] gives an upper bound of the number of grains of sand required to fill the entire universe, using a contemporary estimation of its size.  This would defy the then-held notion that it is impossible to name a number greater than that of the sand on a beach or on the entire world.  In order to do that, he had to devise a [[The Sand Reckoner#Naming large numbers|new numeral scheme]] with much greater range.\n\n[[Pappus of Alexandria]] reports that [[Apollonius of Perga]] developed a simpler system based on [[Exponentiation|powers]] of the myriad; {{overset|\u03b1|\u039c}} was 10,000, {{overset|\u03b2|\u039c}} was 10,000<sup>2</sup> = 100,000,000, {{overset|\u03b3|\u039c}} was 10,000<sup>3</sup> = 10<sup>12</sup> and so on.<ref name=mactutor/>\n\n==Zero==\n[[File:P. Lund, Inv. 35a.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Example of the early Greek symbol for zero (lower right corner) from a 2nd-century papyrus]]\n{{anchor|Hellenistic zero}}<!--linked from \"Number\"-->\n[[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenistic]] [[astronomer]]s extended alphabetic Greek numerals into a [[sexagesimal]] [[positional notation|positional]] [[numeral system|numbering system]] by limiting each position to a maximum value of 50&nbsp;+&nbsp;9 and including a special symbol for [[0 (number)|zero]], which was also used alone like today's modern zero, more than as a simple placeholder. However, the positions were usually limited to the fractional part of a number (called minutes, seconds, thirds, fourths, etc.) \u2014 they were not used for the [[integer|integral]] part of a number. This system was probably adapted from [[Babylonian numerals]] by [[Hipparchus]] {{circa|140 BC}}. It was then used by [[Ptolemy]] ({{circa|140}}), [[Theon of Alexandria|Theon]] ({{circa|380}}) and Theon's daughter [[Hypatia of Alexandria|Hypatia]] (died&nbsp;415).\n\nIn [[Ptolemy's table of chords]], the first fairly extensive trigonometric table, there were 360 rows, portions of which looked as follows:\n\n: <math>\n\\begin{array}{ccc} \\pi\\varepsilon\\varrho\\iota\\varphi\\varepsilon\\varrho\\varepsilon\\iota\\tilde\\omega\\nu & \\overset{\\text{'}}\\varepsilon\\nu\\vartheta\\varepsilon\\iota\\tilde\\omega\\nu & \\overset{\\text{`}}\\varepsilon\\xi\\eta\\kappa\\omicron\\sigma\\tau\\tilde\\omega\\nu \\\\\n\\begin{array}{|l|} \\hline \\pi\\delta\\angle' \\\\  \\pi\\varepsilon \\\\  \\pi\\varepsilon\\angle' \\\\  \\hline  \\pi\\stigma \\\\  \\pi\\stigma\\angle' \\\\  \\pi\\zeta \\\\  \\hline \\end{array} & \\begin{array}{|r|r|r|} \\hline \\pi & \\mu\\alpha & \\gamma \\\\  \\pi\\alpha & \\delta & \\iota\\varepsilon \\\\  \\pi\\alpha & \\kappa\\zeta & \\kappa\\beta \\\\  \\hline \\pi\\alpha & \\nu & \\kappa\\delta \\\\  \\pi\\beta & \\iota\\gamma & \\iota\\vartheta \\\\  \\pi\\beta & \\lambda\\stigma & \\vartheta \\\\  \\hline \\end{array} & \\begin{array}{|r|r|r|r|} \\hline \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\stigma & \\kappa\\varepsilon \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\stigma & \\iota\\delta \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\stigma & \\gamma \\\\  \\hline \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\varepsilon & \\nu\\beta \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\varepsilon & \\mu \\\\  \\circ & \\circ & \\mu\\varepsilon & \\kappa\\vartheta \\\\  \\hline \\end{array}\n\\end{array}\n</math>\nEach number in the first column, labeled {{lang|grc|\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u1ff6\u03bd}}, is the number of degrees of arc on a circle.  Each number in the second column, labeled {{lang|grc|\u03b5\u1f50\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u1ff6\u03bd}}, is the length of the corresponding chord of the circle, when the diameter is 120.  Thus \u03c0\u03b4 represents an 84\u00b0 arc, and the \u2220\u2032 after it means one-half, so that \u03c0\u03b4\u2220\u2032 means {{frac|84|1|2}}\u00b0.  In the next column we see \u03c0&nbsp;\u03bc\u03b1&nbsp;\u03b3, meaning 80&nbsp;+&nbsp;{{sfrac|41|60}}&nbsp;+&nbsp;{{sfrac|3|60<sup>2</sup>}}.  That is the length of the chord corresponding to an arc of {{frac|84|1|2}}\u00b0 when the diameter of the circle is&nbsp;120.  The next column, labeled {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03be\u03b7\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u1ff6\u03bd}}, for \"sixtieths\", is the number to be added to the chord length for each 1\u00b0 increase in the arc, over the span of the next 12\u00b0.  Thus that last column was used for [[linear interpolation]].\n\nThe Greek sexagesimal placeholder or zero symbol changed over time. The symbol used on [[papyrus|papyri]] during the second century was a very small circle with an overbar several diameters long, terminated or not at both ends in various ways. Later, the overbar shortened to only one diameter, similar to the modern ''o'' macron (\u014d) which was still being used in late medieval Arabic manuscripts whenever alphabetic numerals were used. But the overbar was omitted in [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] manuscripts, leaving a bare ''\u03bf'' (omicron). This gradual change from an invented symbol to ''\u03bf'' does not support the hypothesis that the latter was the initial of \u03bf\u1f50\u03b4\u03ad\u03bd meaning \"nothing\".<ref>{{Cite book | edition = 2 | publisher = [[Dover Publications]] | last = Neugebauer | first = Otto | author-link = Otto E. Neugebauer | title = The Exact Sciences in Antiquity | origyear = 1957 | year = 1969 | isbn = 978-0-486-22332-2 | pages = 13\u201314, plate 2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Raymond |last=Mercier|url= http://www.raymondm.co.uk/prog/GreekZeroSign.pdf |title=Consideration of the Greek symbol 'zero' }} Numerous examples</ref> Note that the letter ''\u03bf'' was still used with its original numerical value of 70; however, there was no ambiguity, as 70 could not appear in the fractional part of a number, and zero was usually omitted when it was the integer.\n\nSome of Ptolemy's true zeros appeared in the first line of each of his eclipse tables, where they were a measure of the angular separation between the center of the [[Moon]] and either the center of the [[Sun]] (for [[solar eclipse]]s) or the center of [[Earth]]'s shadow (for [[lunar eclipse]]s). All of these zeros took the form {{nowrap|\u03bf {{!}} \u03bf \u03bf}}, where Ptolemy actually used three of the symbols described in the previous paragraph. The vertical bar (|) indicates that the integral part on the left was in a separate column labeled in the headings of his tables as ''digits'' (of five arc-minutes each), whereas the fractional part was in the next column labeled ''minute of immersion'', meaning sixtieths (and thirty-six-hundredths) of a digit.<ref>''Ptolemy's [[Almagest]]'', translated by [[G. J. Toomer]], Book VI, (Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press, 1998), pp.&nbsp;306\u20137.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Attic numerals]]\n*[[Cyrillic numerals]]\n*[[Gematria]]\n*[[Unicode numerals#Ancient Greek numerals|Greek numerals in Unicode]] (acrophonic, not alphabetic, numerals)\n*[[Isopsephy]]\n*[[Number of the Beast]]\n*[[Alphabetic numeral system]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Greek numerals}}\n* [http://www.russellcottrell.com/greek/utilities/GreekNumberConverter.htm The Greek Number Converter]\n\n{{Greek language}}\n{{Ancient Greece topics}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greek Numerals}}\n[[Category:Numeral systems]]\n[[Category:Numerals]]\n[[Category:Greek mathematics|Numerals]]\n", "name_user": "Joe Kress", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove extraneous characters", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_numerals"}
